careful.meaning: Taking care; attentive to potential danger, error or harm; cautious.

carnival.meaning: Any of a number of festivals held just before the beginning of Lent.

carpet.meaning: A fabric used as a complete floor covering.

carpool.meaning: An arrangement whereby several people travel together in the same car in order to save costs, reduce pollution etc.

carrot.meaning: A vegetable with a nutritious, juicy, sweet root that is often orange in colour, Daucus carota, especially the subspecies sativus in the family Apiaceae.

cattle.meaning: Domesticated bovine animals (cows, bulls, steers etc).

celebration.meaning: The formal performance of a solemn rite, such as Christian sacrament.

cell.meaning: A single-room dwelling for a hermit.

cellar.meaning: An enclosed underground space, often under a building, used for storage or shelter.

cent.meaning: (money) A subunit of currency equal to one-hundredth of the main unit of currency in many countries. Symbol: ¢.

cereal.meaning: A type of grass (such as wheat, rice or oats) cultivated for its edible grains.

ceremony.meaning: A ritual, with religious or cultural significance.

certainly.meaning: In a way which is certain; with certainty.

certificate.meaning: A document containing a certified statement.

chain.meaning: A series of interconnected rings or links usually made of metal.

chairman.meaning: A person presiding over a meeting.

challenging.meaning: To invite (someone) to take part in a competition.

champagne.meaning: A sparkling white wine made from a blend of grapes, especially Chardonnay and pinot, produced in Champagne, France, by the méthode champenoise.

championship.meaning: A competition to determine a champion, especially the final of a series of competitions.

chancellor.meaning: A senior secretary or official with administrative or legal duties, sometimes in charge of some area of government such as finance or justice.

chest.meaning: A box, now usually a large strong box with a secure convex lid.

chief.meaning: A leader or head of a group of people, organisation, etc.

five.example: He wrote a five followed by four zeroes.

fix.example: That plumber's fix is much better than the first one's.

fixed.meaning: To pierce; now generally replaced by transfix.

flag.meaning: A piece of cloth, often decorated with an emblem, used as a visual signal or symbol.

flame.meaning: The visible part of fire; a stream of burning vapour or gas, emitting light and heat.

flash.meaning: A device that produces a short flash of light to help illuminate a scene, mostly for night-time or indoors photography.

flawless.meaning: Without flaws, defects, or shortcomings; perfect.
flawless.example: The pianist’s performance this evening was flawless.

flax.meaning: A plant of the genus Linum, especially Linum usitatissimum, which has a single, slender stalk, about a foot and a half high, with blue flowers. Also known as linseed, especially when referring to the seeds.

flea.meaning: A small, wingless, parasitic insect of the order Siphonaptera, renowned for its bloodsucking habits and jumping abilities.

flee.example: The prisoner tried to flee, but was caught by the guards.

fleet.meaning: A group of vessels or vehicles.

flesh.meaning: The soft tissue of the body, especially muscle and fat.

flexibility.meaning: The quality of being flexible; suppleness; pliability.

flight.example: Most birds are capable of flight.

flip.meaning: A maneuver which rotates an object end over end.
flip.example: The diver did a couple of flips before landing in the pool.

float.meaning: A buoyant device used to support something in water or another liquid.
float.example: Attach the float and the weight to the fishing line, above the hook.

flock.meaning: A large number of birds, especially those gathered together for the purpose of migration.

flood.meaning: A (usually disastrous) overflow of water from a lake or other body of water due to excessive rainfall or other input of water.

floor.meaning: The interior bottom or surface of a house or building; the supporting surface of a room.
floor.example: The room has a wooden floor.

flour.meaning: Powder obtained by grinding or milling cereal grains, especially wheat, or other foodstuffs such as soybeans and potatoes, and used to bake bread, cakes, and pastry.

flow.meaning: A movement in people or things with a particular way in large numbers or amounts

flower.meaning: A colorful, conspicuous structure associated with angiosperms, frequently scented and attracting various insects, and which may or may not be used for sexual reproduction.

fluency.meaning: The quality of smoothness of flow.

fluent.meaning: A continuous variable, especially one with respect to time in Newton's Method of Fluxions.

fluently.meaning: In a fluent manner, as expressing oneself easily, especially in a foreign language.
fluently.example: He lived in Mexico, so he is able to speak Spanish fluently.

fluid.meaning: Any substance which can flow with relative ease, tends to assume the shape of its container, and obeys Bernoulli's principle; a liquid, gas or plasma.

foolish.meaning: (of a person, an action, etc.) Lacking good sense or judgement; unwise.

foolishly.example: He dressed foolishly to entertain the children.

foot.meaning: A biological structure found in many animals that is used for locomotion and that is frequently a separate organ at the terminal part of the leg.

football.meaning: (general) A sport played on foot in which teams attempt to get a ball into a goal or zone defended by the other team.
football.example: Roman and medieval football matches were more violent than any modern type of football.

footnote.meaning: A short piece of text, often numbered, placed at the bottom of a printed page, that adds a comment, citation, reference etc, to a designated part of the main text.
footnote.example: consult the footnotes for more details

forbid.example: Smoking in the restaurant is forbidden.

forbidden.example: Smoking in the restaurant is forbidden.

force.meaning: Strength or energy of body or mind; active power; vigour; might; capacity of exercising an influence or producing an effect.
force.example: the force of an appeal, an argument, or a contract

forcefully.meaning: With either physical of coercive force; in a forceful manner; vigorously; powerfully.

forecast.meaning: An estimation of a future condition.

forehead.meaning: The part of the face above the eyebrows and below the hairline.

foreigner.meaning: A person from a foreign country.

foreman.meaning: The leader of a work crew.

foresee.meaning: To be able to see beforehand: to anticipate; predict.

forest.meaning: A dense uncultivated tract of trees and undergrowth, larger than woods.

forestry.meaning: The science of planting and growing trees in forests.

forever.example: I haven't seen him in forever!

forget.example: I have forgotten most of the things I learned in school.

forgive.meaning: To pardon; to waive any negative feeling or desire for punishment, retribution, or compensation.
forgive.example: Forgive others, not because they deserve forgiveness, but because you deserve peace.

fork.meaning: A pronged tool having a long straight handle, used for digging, lifting, throwing etc.

formally.example: He was dressed too formally for the occasion.

format.meaning: The layout of a publication or document.

former.example: A former president;  the former East Germany

formerly.meaning: At some time in the past

formidable.meaning: Causing fear, dread, awe, or discouragement as a result of size, strength, or some other impressive feature; commanding respect; causing wonder or astonishment.

frankly.meaning: (manner) In a frank, open or (too) honest manner.
frankly.example: He spoke frankly about the economy.

fraud.meaning: The crime of stealing or otherwise illegally obtaining money by use of deception tactics.

freedom.meaning: The state of being free, of not being imprisoned or enslaved.
freedom.example: Having recently been released from prison, he didn't know what to do with his newfound freedom.

freeze.meaning: Especially of a liquid, to become solid due to low temperature.

freezer.meaning: An appliance or room used to store food or other perishable items at temperatures below 0° Celsius (32° Fahrenheit).

freezing.meaning: Especially of a liquid, to become solid due to low temperature.

frequency.meaning: The rate of occurrence of anything; the relationship between incidence and time period.
frequency.example: The frequency of bus service has been improved from one every 15 to one every 12 minutes.

frequent.example: I am a frequent visitor to that city.

fresh.meaning: A rush of water, along a river or onto the land; a flood.

freshman.meaning: A novice; one in the rudiments of knowledge.

friend.meaning: A person other than a family member, spouse or lover whose company one enjoys and towards whom one feels affection.
friend.example: John and I have been friends ever since we were roommates at college.   Trust is important between friends.   I used to find it hard to make friends when I was shy.

friendly.meaning: A game which is of no consequence in terms of ranking, betting etc.

frigate.meaning: An obsolete type of sailing warship with a single continuous gun deck, typically used for patrolling, blockading, etc, but not in line of battle.

fright.meaning: A state of terror excited by the sudden appearance of danger; sudden and violent fear, usually of short duration; a sudden alarm.

frighten.example: Avery puts a sheet over her head, pretending to be a ghost to frighten Emily.

fully.meaning: In a full manner; without lack or defect.

fume.meaning: A gas or vapour/vapor that is strong-smelling or dangerous to inhale.
fume.example: Don't stand around in there breathing the fumes while the adhesive cures.

function.meaning: What something does or is used for.

functional.meaning: A function that takes a function as its argument; More precisely: A function y=f(x) whose argument x varies in a space of (real valued, complex valued) functions and whose value belongs to a monodimensional space. An example: the definite integration of integrable real functions in a real interval.

functionality.meaning: The ability to perform a task or function; that set of functions that something is able or equipped to perform.

fund.meaning: A sum or source of money.
fund.example: a fund for the maintenance of underprivileged students

fundamental.meaning: (usually in the plural) A leading or primary principle, rule, law, or article, which serves as the groundwork of a system; an essential part

funeral.meaning: A ceremony to honour and remember a deceased person. Often distinguished from a memorial service by the presence of the body of the deceased.
funeral.example: Many mourners turned up at the local artist's funeral to pay homage.

funk.meaning: Foul or unpleasant smell, especially body odor.

fur.meaning: The hairy coat of various mammal species, especially when fine, soft and thick.

furious.example: a furious animal; parent furious at their child's behaviour

furiously.example: He glared furiously at the offender.

furnish.meaning: Material used to create an engineered product.

furniture.meaning: Large movable item(s), usually in a room, which enhance(s) the room's characteristics, functionally or decoratively.

furthermore.meaning: In addition; besides; what's more; used to denote additional information.

fuss.meaning: Excessive activity, worry, bother, or talk about something.
fuss.example: They made a big fuss about the wedding plans.

future.meaning: The time ahead; those moments yet to be experienced.

gaiety.meaning: The state of being happy or merry.
gaiety.example: The decorations added greatly to the gaiety of the room.

gall.meaning: Bile, especially that of an animal; the greenish, profoundly bitter-tasting fluid found in bile ducts and gall bladders, structures associated with the liver.

gallery.meaning: An institution, building, or room for the exhibition and conservation of works of art.

gallon.meaning: A unit of volume, equivalent to eight pints

gambling.meaning: To take a risk, with the potential of a positive outcome.

gangster.meaning: A member of a criminal or street gang.

gap.meaning: An opening in anything made by breaking or parting.

garage.meaning: A building (or section of a building) used to store a car or cars, tools and other miscellaneous items.

garbage.meaning: Food waste material of any kind.

garden.meaning: An outdoor area containing one or more types of plants, usually plants grown for food or ornamental purposes.
garden.example: a vegetable garden  a flower garden

gardener.meaning: One who gardens; one who grows plants or cultivates a garden.

gardening.meaning: To grow plants in a garden; to create or maintain a garden.
gardening.example: I love to garden — this year I'm going to plant some daffodils.

garlic.meaning: A plant, Allium sativum, related to the onion, having a pungent bulb much used in cooking.

gas.meaning: Matter in a state intermediate between liquid and plasma that can be contained only if it is fully surrounded by a solid (or in a bubble of liquid) (or held together by gravitational pull); it can condense into a liquid, or can (rarely) become a solid directly.

gasp.meaning: A short, sudden intake of breath.
gasp.example: The audience gave a gasp of astonishment

gate.meaning: A doorlike structure outside a house.

gateway.meaning: An entrance capable of being blocked by use of a gate.

gather.meaning: A plait or fold in cloth, made by drawing a thread through it; a pucker.

gaudy.meaning: One of the large beads in the rosary at which the paternoster is recited.

gay.meaning: (chiefly in plural or attributive) A homosexual, especially a male homosexual; see also lesbian.

gaze.meaning: A fixed look; a look of eagerness, wonder, or admiration; a continued look of attention.

gear.meaning: Equipment or paraphernalia, especially that used for an athletic endeavor.

gee.meaning: A general exclamation of surprise or frustration.

general.meaning: A general fact or proposition; a generality.

generally.example: It is generally known that the Earth is round.

generate.meaning: To bring into being; give rise to.

generosity.meaning: The trait of being willing to donate money, time or resources.

generously.meaning: In a generous manner, in a way that is giving or ample.

genetically.meaning: In terms of origin or development.

genetics.meaning: The branch of biology that deals with the transmission and variation of inherited characteristics, in particular chromosomes and DNA.

geographical.meaning: A move to another place in the hope of curing an addiction etc.

geography.meaning: A description of the earth: a treatise or textbook on geography; an atlas or gazetteer.

germ.meaning: The small mass of cells from which a new organism develops; a seed, bud or spore.

gesture.meaning: A motion of the limbs or body, especially one made to emphasize speech.

ghost.meaning: The spirit; the soul of man.

giant.meaning: A mythical human of very great size.

gift.meaning: Something given to another voluntarily, without charge.

girl.meaning: A female child, adolescent, or a young woman.

globe.example: the globe of the eye; the globe of a lamp

glow.meaning: The state of a glowing object.

goal.meaning: A result that one is attempting to achieve.

god.meaning: A being such as a monotheistic God: a single divine creator and ruler of the universe.

golden.meaning: Kyphosus vaigiensis, a fish found in southeast Asia.

golf.meaning: A ball game played by individuals competing against one another in which the object is to hit a ball into each of a series of (usually 18 or nine) holes in the minimum number of strokes.

good morning.meaning: An exercise performed by bending forward at the waist and then returning to a standing posture, while bearing a barbell across the shoulders.

goodness.meaning: The state or characteristic of being good.

goods.meaning: The forces or behaviours that are the enemy of evil. Usually consists of helping others and general benevolence.

goodwill.meaning: A favorably disposed attitude toward someone or something.

gook.meaning: A person of Far Eastern or Oceanian descent, especially a Vietnamese, Filipino, Chinese, Japanese or Korean person.

gorgeous.meaning: (of a person or place) Very beautiful.

gossip.meaning: Someone who likes to talk about other people's private or personal business.

governor.meaning: The chief executive officer of a first-level division of a country.

grace.example: The Princess brought grace to an otherwise dull and boring party.

graceful.meaning: Having or showing grace in movement, shape, or proportion.

grade.example: I gave him a good grade for effort.

gradual.meaning: An antiphon or responsory after the epistle, in the Mass, which was sung on the steps, or while the deacon ascended the steps.

gradually.meaning: In a gradual manner; making slow progress; slowly.

graduate.meaning: A person who is recognized by a university as having completed the requirements of a degree studied at the institution.

graduation.meaning: The action or process of graduating and receiving a diploma for completing a course of study (such as from an educational institution).

grain.meaning: The harvested seeds of various grass food crops eg: wheat, corn, barley.
grain.example: We stored a thousand tons of grain for the winter.

grammar.meaning: A system of rules and principles for speaking and writing a language.

grand.meaning: (plural "grand") A thousand of some unit of currency, such as dollars or pounds. (Compare G.)

grandparent.meaning: To be, or act as, a grandfather to.

granny.example: I'm going to be a granny.

grant.meaning: The act of granting; a bestowing or conferring; concession; allowance; permission.

grape.meaning: A small, round, smooth-skinned edible fruit, usually purple, red, or green, that grows in bunches on vines of genus Vitis.

grass.meaning: Any plant of the family Poaceae, characterized by leaves that arise from nodes in the stem and leaf bases that wrap around the stem, especially those grown as ground cover rather than for grain.

grateful.example: I'm grateful that you helped me out.

grin.meaning: A smile in which the lips are parted to reveal the teeth.

grip.meaning: To take hold of, particularly with the hand.

grocery store.meaning: A store where groceries can be purchased; supermarket.

groom.meaning: A man who is about to marry.

ground.meaning: The surface of the Earth, as opposed to the sky or water or underground.

growing.meaning: To become larger, to increase in magnitude.

guard.meaning: A person who, or thing that, protects or watches over something.

guest.meaning: A recipient of hospitality, specifically someone staying by invitation at the house of another.
guest.example: The guests were let in by the butler.

guidance.meaning: The act or process of guiding.

guide.meaning: Someone who guides, especially someone hired to show people around a place or an institution and offer information and explanation.
guide.example: The guide led us around the museum and explained the exhibits.

guidebook.meaning: A book that provides guidance, but especially one designed for travellers which provides local tourist information about a particular country or area.

guideline.meaning: A non-specific rule or principle that provides direction to action or behaviour.
guideline.example: He considered the Ten Commandments more a guideline than a requirement.

guilty.meaning: A plea by a defendant who does not contest a charge.

guitar.meaning: A stringed musical instrument, of European origin, usually with a fretted fingerboard and six strings, played with the fingers or a plectrum (guitar pick).

hairdryer.meaning: A small electrical appliance for drying hair, by generating a stream of hot air.

hairy.meaning: Of a person, having a lot of hair on the body.

half.meaning: One of two usually roughly equal parts into which anything may be divided, or considered as divided.
half.example: I ate the slightly smaller half of the apple.

half-price.meaning: For sale at half the normal price.

hall.example: The drinking fountain was out in the hall.

ham.meaning: The region back of the knee joint; the popliteal space; the hock.

hamburger.meaning: A hot sandwich consisting of a patty of cooked ground beef or a meat substitute, in a sliced bun, sometimes also containing salad vegetables, condiments, or both.

hammer.meaning: A tool with a heavy head and a handle used for pounding.
hammer.example: Bobby used a hammer and nails to fix the two planks together

hand.meaning: The part of the forelimb below the forearm or wrist in a human, and the corresponding part in many other animals.

handball.meaning: A team sport where two teams of seven players each (six players and a goalkeeper) pass and bounce a ball trying to throw it in the goal of the opposing team.

hand-held.meaning: A personal digital assistant or video game console that is small enough to be held in the hands.

handicap.meaning: Something that prevents, hampers, or hinders.

handicapped.meaning: To encumber with a handicap in any contest.

handicraft.meaning: A trade requiring skill of hand; manual occupation; handcraft.

handkerchief.meaning: A piece of cloth, usually square and often fine and elegant, carried for wiping the face, eyes, nose or hands.

handle.meaning: The part of an object which is (designed to be) held in the hand when used or moved.

handout.meaning: A worksheet, leaflet, or pamphlet that is given out (usually by hand) for a certain use.

handrail.meaning: A rail which can be held, such as on the side of a staircase, ramp or other walkway, and serving as a support or guard.

handshake.meaning: The grasping of hands by two people when greeting, leave-taking, or making an agreement.

handwriting.meaning: To write something manually, normally used to emphasise that it is not being typed.

hang.meaning: The way in which something hangs.
hang.example: This skirt has a nice hang.

hanging.example: The lights hung from the ceiling.

haste.example: We were running late so we finished our meal in haste.

hastily.meaning: In a hasty manner; quickly, hurriedly.

hasty.meaning: Acting in haste; being too hurried or quick

hat.meaning: A covering for the head, often in the approximate form of a cone or a cylinder closed at its top end, and sometimes having a brim and other decoration.

hatch.meaning: A horizontal door in a floor or ceiling.

hatching.meaning: To close with a hatch or hatches.

hate.example: One of my pet hates is traffic wardens.

haunt.meaning: A place at which one is regularly found; a habitation or hangout.

haunting.meaning: To inhabit, or visit frequently (most often used in reference to ghosts).
haunting.example: A couple of ghosts haunt the old, burnt-down house.

haven.meaning: A harbour or anchorage protected from the sea.

hay.meaning: Grass cut and dried for use as animal fodder.

hazard.meaning: The chance of suffering harm; danger, peril, risk of loss.
hazard.example: He encountered the enemy at the hazard of his reputation and life.

hazardous.meaning: Risky, dangerous, with the nature of a hazard.

he.meaning: The game of tag, or it, in which the player attempting to catch the others is called "he".

head.meaning: The part of the body of an animal or human which contains the brain, mouth and main sense organs.
head.example: Be careful when you pet that dog on the head; it may bite.

headache.meaning: A pain or ache in the head.

headline.meaning: The heading or title of a magazine or newspaper article.
headline.example: The headline on today's newspaper reads "John Doe Wins Wood-Splitting Competition."

headphone.meaning: A listening device placed or worn in the ear, usually sold in pairs
headphone.example: She handed me one headphone so I could listen too.

headquarters.meaning: The military installation from which troops are commanded and orders are issued; the military unit consisting of a commander and his support staff.

headteacher.meaning: The most senior teacher in a school who is responsible for its management and administration.
headteacher.example: I had to go and see the headteacher about my attitude.

heal.meaning: A spell or ability that restores hit points or removes a status ailment.

healing.meaning: The process where the cells in the body regenerate and repair themselves.

hedge.meaning: A thicket of bushes or other shrubbery, especially one planted as a fence between two portions of land, or to separate the parts of a garden.
hedge.example: He trims the hedge once a week.

heel.meaning: The rear part of the foot, where it joins the leg.

height.meaning: The distance from the base of something to the top.

helicopter.meaning: An aircraft that is borne along by one or more sets of long rotating blades which allow it to hover, move in any direction including reverse, or land; and typically having a smaller set of blades on its tail that stabilize the aircraft.

helmet.meaning: A protective head covering, usually part of armour.

help.meaning: Action given to provide assistance; aid.
help.example: I need some help with my homework.

hemp.meaning: A tall annual herb, Cannabis sativa, native to Asia.

her.example: I think this bird is a him, but it may be a her.

herb.meaning: Any green, leafy plant, or parts thereof, used to flavour or season food.

herd.meaning: A number of domestic animals assembled together under the watch or ownership of a keeper.

here.example: An Alzheimer patient's here may in his mind be anywhere he called home in the time he presently re-lives.

heritage.meaning: An inheritance; property that may be inherited.

hero.meaning: Somebody who possesses great bravery and carries out extraordinary or noble deeds.

hers.example: I think this bird is a him, but it may be a her.

herself.meaning: (reflexive pronoun) Her; the female object of a verb or preposition that also appears as the subject.

hesitate.meaning: To stop or pause respecting decision or action; to be in suspense or uncertainty as to a determination.
hesitate.example: He hesitated whether to accept the offer or not; men often hesitate in forming a judgment.

hi.meaning: The word "hi" used as a greeting.
hi.example: I didn't even get a hi.

hidden.meaning: Located or positioned out of sight; not visually apparent.

hide.meaning: To put (something) in a place where it will be harder to discover or out of sight.
hide.example: He hides his magazines under the bed.

high.meaning: A high point or position, literally or figuratively; an elevated place; a superior region; a height; the sky; heaven.

high school.meaning: An institution which provides all or part of secondary education.

highlight.meaning: An area or a spot in a drawing, painting, or photograph that is strongly illuminated.

highly.meaning: In a high or esteemed manner.

hit.meaning: A blow; a punch; a striking against; the collision of one body against another; the stroke that touches anything.

hobby.meaning: An activity that one enjoys doing in one's spare time.
hobby.example: I like to collect stamps from different countries as a hobby.

hockey.meaning: Ice hockey, a game on ice in which two teams of six players skate and try to score by shooting a puck into the opposing team's net, using their sticks.

miracle.meaning: An event that appears inexplicable by the laws of nature and so is held to be supernatural in origin.
miracle.example: An example of a miracle associated with Muhammad is the splitting of the moon.

mirror.meaning: A smooth surface, usually made of glass with reflective material painted on the underside, that reflects light so as to give an image of what is in front of it.
mirror.example: I had a look in the mirror to see if the blood had come off my face.

mischief.meaning: Conduct that playfully causes petty annoyance.

misconception.meaning: A mistaken belief, a wrong idea
misconception.example: He had the misconception that the word "misconception" meant becoming pregnant with a girl.

misery.meaning: Great unhappiness; extreme pain of body or mind; wretchedness; distress; woe.
misery.example: Ever since his wife left him you can see the misery on his face.

misfortune.example: It was my fortune, or misfortune, to be called to the office of Chief Executive without any previous political training. - Ulysses S. Grant

mislead.meaning: To lead astray, in a false direction.

misleading.meaning: To lead astray, in a false direction.

missile.meaning: Any object used as a weapon by being thrown or fired through the air, such as stone, arrow or bullet.
missile.example: The Rhodians, who used leaden bullets, were able to project their missiles twice as far as the Persian slingers, who used large stones.

model.meaning: A person who serves as a subject for artwork or fashion, usually in the medium of photography but also for painting or drawing.
model.example: The beautiful model had her face on the cover of almost every fashion magazine imaginable.

modem.meaning: A device that encodes digital computer signals into analog/analogue telephone signals and vice versa and allows computers to communicate over a phone line.

moderate.meaning: One who holds an intermediate position between extremes, as in politics.
moderate.example: The moderates are the natural advocates of ecumenism against the fanatics of their churches.

modern.meaning: Someone who lives in modern times.

modest.meaning: Not bragging or boasting about oneself or one's achievements; unpretentious, humble.

modification.meaning: The form of existence belonging to a particular object, entity etc.; a mode of being.

mogul.meaning: A rich or powerful person; a magnate.

moisture.meaning: That which moistens or makes damp or wet; exuding fluid; liquid in small quantity.

molecule.meaning: The smallest particle of a specific element or compound that retains the chemical properties of that element or compound; two or more atoms held together by chemical bonds.
molecule.example: Hydrogen chloride is a diatomic molecule, consisting of a hydrogen atom and a chlorine atom.

moment.meaning: A brief, unspecified amount of time.
moment.example: Wait a moment, while I lock the front door.

momentarily.meaning: (manner) In a momentary manner; for a moment or instant.

monastery.meaning: Building for housing monks or others who have taken religious vows

money.meaning: A legally or socially binding conceptual contract of entitlement to wealth, void of intrinsic value, payable for all debts and taxes, and regulated in supply.

monitor.meaning: Someone who watches over something; a person in charge of something or someone.
monitor.example: The camp monitors look after the children during the night, when the teachers are asleep.

monk.meaning: A male member of a monastic order who has devoted his life for religious service.

monkey.meaning: Any member of the clade Simiiformes not also of the clade Hominoidea containing humans and apes, from which they are usually, but not universally, distinguished by smaller size, a tail, and cheek pouches.
monkey.example: He had been visiting an area zoo when a monkey swung from its tree perch, swiped his glasses and hurled them into a hippo hole.

month.meaning: A period into which a year is divided, historically based on the phases of the moon.

monthly.meaning: A publication that is published once a month.

monument.meaning: A structure built for commemorative or symbolic reasons, or as a memorial; a commemoration.
monument.example: There is a monument on the town green to the soldiers who died in World War I.

mood.meaning: A mental or emotional state, composure.
mood.example: I've been in a bad mood since I dumped my boyfriend.

moody.meaning: Given to sudden or frequent changes of mind; temperamental.

moon.meaning: (by extension of Moon) Any natural satellite of a planet.
moon.example: That's no moon, you idiot... it's a space station!

moonlight.meaning: (sometimes attributive) The light reflected from the Moon.

moonscape.meaning: A view of an area of the Moon

moral.meaning: (of a narrative) The ethical significance or practical lesson.

morality.meaning: Recognition of the distinction between good and evil or between right and wrong; respect for and obedience to the rules of right conduct; the mental disposition or characteristic of behaving in a manner intended to produce morally good results.

morally.meaning: In terms of morals or ethics.
morally.example: Morally, it is a difficult issue to deal with.

more.meaning: To a greater degree or extent.
more.example: I could no more climb that than fly!

moreover.meaning: In addition to what has been said; furthermore; additionally.

morning.meaning: The part of the day from dawn to noon.

mortal.meaning: A human; someone susceptible to death.
mortal.example: Her wisdom was beyond that of a mere mortal.

mortar.meaning: A mixture of lime or cement, sand and water used for bonding building blocks.

mortgage.meaning: A special form of secured loan where the purpose of the loan must be specified to the lender, to purchase assets that must be fixed (not movable) property, such as a house or piece of farm land. The assets are registered as the legal property of the borrower but the lender can seize them and dispose of them if they are not satisfied with the manner in which the repayment of the loan is conducted by the borrower. Once the loan is fully repaid, the lender loses this right of seizure and the assets are then deemed to be unencumbered.
mortgage.example: We're renting a property in the city centre because we can't afford to get a mortgage yet.

mortify.meaning: To discipline (one's body, appetites etc.) by suppressing desires; to practise abstinence on.
mortify.example: Some people seek sainthood by mortifying the body.

mosque.meaning: A place of worship for Muslims, often having at least one minaret; a masjid.
mosque.example: There's a mosque near where I live.

mosquito.meaning: A small flying insect of the family Culicidae, the females of which bite humans and animals and suck blood, leaving an itching bump on the skin, and sometimes carrying diseases like malaria and yellow fever.

moss.meaning: Any of various small, green, seedless plants growing on the ground or on the surfaces of trees, stones, etc.; now specifically, a plant of the phylum Bryophyta (formerly division Musci).

most.example: The most I can offer for the house is $150,000.

mostly.meaning: Mainly or chiefly; for the most part; usually, generally, on the whole.
mostly.example: They're mostly good people, although they have made a few mistakes.

mother.meaning: A (human) female who has given birth to a baby
mother.example: He had something of his mother in him.

motion.meaning: A state of progression from one place to another.

motionless.meaning: At rest, stationary, immobile, not moving.

motivate.meaning: To provide someone with an incentive to do something; to encourage.
motivate.example: The weekly staff meeting was meant to motivate employees.

motivated.meaning: To provide someone with an incentive to do something; to encourage.
motivated.example: The weekly staff meeting was meant to motivate employees.

motivation.meaning: Willingness of action especially in behavior.

motive.meaning: An idea or communication that makes one want to act, especially from spiritual sources; a divine prompting.

motor.meaning: A machine or device that converts other energy forms into mechanical energy, or imparts motion.

motorcycle.meaning: An open-seated motor vehicle with handlebars instead of a steering wheel, and having two (or sometimes three) wheels.

motorist.meaning: One who drives a motor vehicle.

motorway.meaning: (parts of Australia) A broad highway designed for high speed traffic, having restrictions on the vehicle types permitted and merging lanes instead of cross traffic; in parts of the United States and other places called freeway.

motto.meaning: A sentence, phrase, or word, forming part of an heraldic achievement.

mountain.meaning: An elevation of land of considerable dimensions rising more or less abruptly, forming a conspicuous figure in the landscape, usually having a small extent of surface at its summit.
mountain.example: We spent the weekend hiking in the mountains.

mournful.meaning: Filled with grief or sadness; being in a state in which one mourns.

mouse.meaning: Any small rodent of the genus Mus.

mouth.meaning: The opening of a creature through which food is ingested.
mouth.example: "Open your mouth and say 'aah'," directed the doctor.

move.meaning: The act of moving; a movement.
move.example: A slight move of the tiller, and the boat will go off course.

movement.meaning: Physical motion between points in space.
movement.example: I saw a movement in that grass on the hill.

mover.meaning: Someone who or something that moves.

movie.meaning: A recorded sequence of images displayed on a screen at a rate sufficiently fast to create the appearance of motion.

moving.meaning: To change place or posture; to go, in any manner, from one place or position to another.

mud.meaning: A mixture of water and soil or fine grained sediment.

muddy.example: If you muddy your shoes don't wear them inside.

mug.meaning: A large cup for hot liquids, usually having a handle and used without a saucer.

mule.meaning: The generally sterile male or female hybrid offspring of a male donkey and a female horse.

multiple.meaning: A whole number that can be divided by another number with no remainder.

multiply.meaning: An act or instance of multiplying.

mumble.meaning: A quiet or unintelligible vocalization; a low tone of voice.
mumble.example: All I could hear was a mumble from the next room.

murder.meaning: The crime of deliberately killing another person without justification.
murder.example: The defendant was charged with murder.

murmur.meaning: Any low, indistinct sound, like that of running water.

muscle.meaning: A contractile form of tissue which animals use to effect movement.
muscle.example: Muscle consists largely of actin and myosin filaments.

museum.meaning: A building or institution dedicated to the acquisition, conservation, study, exhibition, and educational interpretation of objects having scientific, historical, cultural or artistic value.

mushroom.meaning: Any of the fleshy fruiting bodies of fungi typically produced above ground on soil or on their food sources (such as decaying wood).
mushroom.example: Some mushrooms are edible and taste good, while others are poisonous and taste foul.

music.meaning: A series of sounds organized in time, employing melody, harmony, tempo etc. usually to convey a mood.
music.example: I keep listening to this music because it's a masterpiece.

musical.meaning: A stage performance, show or film that involves singing, dancing and musical numbers performed by the cast as well as acting.

musician.meaning: A composer, conductor, or performer of music; specifically, a person who sings and/or plays a musical instrument as a hobby, an occupation, or a profession.

must.meaning: Something that is mandatory or required.
must.example: If you'll be out all day, a map is a must.

mustard.meaning: A plant of certain species of the genus Brassica, or of related genera (especially Sinapis alba, in the family Brassicaceae, with yellow flowers, and linear seed pods).

mutability.meaning: The quality or state of being mutable.

mutable.meaning: Something mutable; a variable or value that can change.

mutter.meaning: A repressed or obscure utterance; an instance of muttering.
mutter.example: The prisoners were docile, and accepted their lot with barely a mutter.

mutton.meaning: The flesh of sheep used as food.

my.meaning: Used to express surprise, shock or amazement.
my.example: My, what big teeth you have!

myself.meaning: (reflexive pronoun) Me, as direct or indirect object the speaker as the object of a verb or preposition, when the speaker is also the subject.

mysterious.example: He received a mysterious phone call this morning.

mystery.meaning: Something secret or unexplainable; an unknown.
mystery.example: The truth behind the events remains a mystery.

mystify.meaning: To thoroughly confuse, befuddle, or bewilder.
mystify.example: Solar eclipses continued to mystify ancient humans for thousands of years.

myth.meaning: A traditional story which embodies a belief regarding some fact or phenomenon of experience, and in which often the forces of nature and of the soul are personified; a sacred narrative regarding a god, a hero, the origin of the world or of a people, etc.

nail.meaning: The thin, horny plate at the ends of fingers and toes on humans and some other animals.
nail.example: When I'm nervous I bite my nails.

naked.example: She was as naked as the day she was born.

name.meaning: Any nounal word or phrase which indicates a particular person, place, class, or thing.
name.example: I've never liked the name my parents gave me so I changed it at the age of twenty.

nap.meaning: A short period of sleep, especially one during the day.

napkin.meaning: A serviette; a (usually rectangular) piece of cloth or paper used at the table for wiping the mouth and hands for cleanliness while eating.

narrate.meaning: To relate (a story or series of events) in speech or writing.

narrative.meaning: The systematic recitation of an event or series of events.

narrator.meaning: One who narrates or tells stories.

narrow.meaning: (chiefly in the plural) A narrow passage, especially a contracted part of a stream, lake, or sea; a strait connecting two bodies of water.
narrow.example: the narrows of New York harbor

narrowly.meaning: In a narrow manner; without flexibility or latitude.
narrowly.example: They regarded the new idea rather narrowly.

nasty.example: Processed foods are full of aspartame and other nasties.

nation.meaning: A historically constituted, stable community of people, formed on the basis of a common language, territory, economic life, ethnicity and/or psychological make-up manifested in a common culture.
nation.example: The Kurdish people constitute a nation in the Middle East

national.example: The diplomats were advised not to interact with any foreign nationals except on official duty.

nationalist.example: You are either a globalist or a nationalist; one cannot be both.

nationality.meaning: Membership of a particular nation or state, by origin, birth, naturalization, ownership, allegiance or otherwise.

nationwide.example: There was a nationwide search on for the bankrobbers.

native.meaning: An aboriginal inhabitant of a region colonized by English-speaking people; in particular:

neck.meaning: The part of the body connecting the head and the trunk found in humans and some animals.

necklace.meaning: An article of jewelry that is worn around the neck, most often made of a string of precious metal, pearls, gems, beads or shells, and sometimes having a pendant attached.

need.meaning: A requirement for something; something needed.
need.example: I've always tried to have few needs beyond food, clothing and shelter.

needle.meaning: A fine, sharp implement usually for piercing such as sewing, or knitting, acupuncture, tattooing, body piercing, medical injections, etc.
needle.example: The seamstress threaded the needle to sew on a button.

needless.example: This new project of yours will only be a needless expense.

needy.example: Needy people want to give too, but have few material goods to offer.

negative.meaning: Refusal or withholding of assents; prohibition, veto

negatively.meaning: In a negative manner; so as to be damaging or not positive.

negotiate.meaning: To confer with others in order to come to terms or reach an agreement.

negotiation.meaning: The process of achieving agreement through discussion.

neither.example: Just as you would not correct it, neither would I.

nephew.meaning: A son of one's sibling, brother-in-law, or sister-in-law; either a son of one's brother (fraternal nephew) or a son of one's sister (sororal nephew).

nerve.meaning: A bundle of neurons with their connective tissue sheaths, blood vessels and lymphatics.
nerve.example: The nerves can be seen through the skin.

nerves.meaning: A bundle of neurons with their connective tissue sheaths, blood vessels and lymphatics.
nerves.example: The nerves can be seen through the skin.

nervously.meaning: In a nervous manner; feeling or displaying nervousness.
nervously.example: He paced nervously as he waited for the important phone call.

nervousness.meaning: The state or quality of being nervous.

ness.meaning: A promontory; a cape or headland. (Frequently used as a suffix in placenames.)

network.meaning: A fabric or structure of fibrous elements attached to each other at regular intervals.

neurosis.meaning: A mental disorder, less severe than psychosis, marked by anxiety or fear which differ from normal measures by their intensity, which disorder results from a failure to compromise or properly adjust during the developmental stages of life, between normal human instinctual impulses and the demands of human society.

neutral.meaning: A nonaligned state, or a member of such a state.

never.meaning: At no time; on no occasion; in no circumstance.
never.example: I finally finished, and I never want to do that again.

nevertheless.meaning: In spite of what preceded; yet.

new.example: Out with the old, in with the new.

newcomer.meaning: One who has recently come to a community; a recent arrival.

newly.meaning: Very recently; in the immediate past.
newly.example: She smelled the newly budding flowers.

news.example: Is there any news about the storm?

newscaster.meaning: One who delivers the news for broadcast on television, radio, etc; a newsreader.

newspaper.meaning: A publication, usually published daily or weekly and usually printed on cheap, low-quality paper, containing news and other articles.

newsworthy.meaning: Interesting enough to be reported as a news

next.meaning: The one that follows after this one.
next.example: Next, please, don't hold up the queue!

next door.meaning: (usually postpositive) That is in an adjacent place; that is located next door.

next to.meaning: Beside, alongside, by, adjacent to, or near.

next-door.meaning: In an adjacent building, room or place.

nickname.meaning: A familiar, invented given name for a person or thing used instead of the actual name of the person or thing.

niece.meaning: A daughter of one’s sibling, brother-in-law, or sister-in-law; either the daughter of one's brother ("fraternal niece"), or of one's sister ("sororal niece").
niece.example: My niece just celebrated her 15th birthday.

night.meaning: The period between sunset and sunrise, when a location faces far away from the sun, thus when the sky is dark.
night.example: How do you sleep at night when you attack your kids like that!?

nightclub.meaning: A public or private establishment that is open late at night to provide entertainment, food, drink, music and/or dancing.

nightlife.example: Rio de Janeiro boasts the best nightlife in South America.

nightmare.meaning: A demon or monster, thought to plague people while they slept and cause a feeling of suffocation and terror during sleep.

nineteen.meaning: The cardinal number occurring after eighteen and before twenty, represented in Roman numerals as XIX and in Arabic numerals as 19. It is the last/largest of the "teens".

ninety.meaning: The cardinal number occurring after eighty-nine and before ninety-one, represented in Roman numerals as XC and in Arabic numerals as 90.

no.meaning: A negating expression; an answer that shows disagreement or disapproval

no one.meaning: Used in contrast to anyone, someone or everyone: not one person; nobody.
no one.example: We went to the store but no one was there.

nobility.meaning: A noble or privileged social class, historically accompanied by a hereditary title; aristocracy.

noble.meaning: An aristocrat; one of aristocratic blood.
noble.example: This country house was occupied by nobles in the 16th century.

normally.meaning: Under normal conditions or circumstances; usually; most of the time
normally.example: Normally, I eat breakfast at 6am, but today, I got up late and didn't eat until 9.

north.meaning: One of the four major compass points, specifically 0°, directed toward the North Pole, and conventionally upwards on a map, abbreviated as N.
north.example: Minnesota is in the north of the USA.

northeast.meaning: The compass point halfway between north and east, specifically 45°, abbreviated as NE.

northeastern.meaning: Of, related to, located in, or from the northeast.

northern.meaning: An inhabitant of the northern regions.

northward.meaning: The direction or area lying to the north of a place.

northwest.meaning: The compass point halfway between north and west, bearing 315°, abbreviated as NW.

northwestern.meaning: Of or pertaining to the northwest; from or to in such a direction.

nose.meaning: A protuberance on the face housing the nostrils, which are used to breathe or smell.
nose.example: She has a cold in the nose.

nostril.meaning: Either of the two orifices located on the nose (or on the beak of a bird); used as a passage for air and other gases to travel the nasal passages.

not.meaning: A unary operation on logical values that changes true to false, and false to true.

notebook.meaning: A book in which notes or memoranda are written.

nothing.meaning: Something trifling, or of no consequence or importance.

notice.example: He took no notice of the changes, and went on as though nothing had happened.

noticeable.meaning: Capable of being seen or noticed.

noticeboard.meaning: A board, hanging on a wall, on which notices and announcements are posted.

notion.meaning: Mental apprehension of whatever may be known, thought, or imagined; idea, concept.

notorious.meaning: Widely known, especially for something negative; infamous.

nought.meaning: Nothing; something which does not exist.

noun.meaning: (grammar, narrow sense) A word that can be used to refer to a person, animal, place, thing, phenomenon, substance, quality, or idea; one of the basic parts of speech in many languages, including English.

nourishment.meaning: The act of nourishing or the state of being nourished

novel.meaning: Newly made, formed or evolved; having no precedent; of recent origin; new.

novelty.meaning: The state of being new or novel; newness.

nowadays.meaning: At the present time; in the current era.

nowhere.example: They went on a cruise to nowhere.

nucleus.meaning: The core, central part of something, around which other elements are assembled.

number.meaning: An abstract entity used to describe quantity.
number.example: Zero, one, −1, 2.5, and pi are all numbers.

numerous.example: There are numerous definitions of the word 'man'.

nursery.meaning: A place where nursing or the raising of children is carried on.

nut.example: There are many sort of nuts: peanuts, cashews, pistachios, Brazil nuts and more.

nutrient.meaning: A source of nourishment, such as food, that can be metabolized by an organism to give energy and build tissue.

nutrition.meaning: The organic process by which an organism assimilates food and uses it for growth and maintenance.

nutritious.meaning: (of food or drink) Providing nutrients; healthy to eat.

nutshell.meaning: The shell that surrounds the kernel of a nut.

oak.meaning: A deciduous tree with distinctive deeply lobed leaves, acorns, and notably strong wood, typically of England and northeastern North America, included in genus Quercus.

oath.meaning: A solemn pledge or promise, appealing to a deity, a ruler, or another entity (not necessarily present) to attest to the truth of a statement or sincerity of one's desire to fulfill a contract or promise.

obedience.example: Obedience is essential in any army.

obey.meaning: To do as ordered by (a person, institution etc), to act according to the bidding of.

obituary.meaning: A brief notice of a person’s death, as published in a newspaper.

object.meaning: A thing that has physical existence.

objective.meaning: A material object that physically exists.

o'clock.meaning: (modifying a numeral, one to twelve) In conjunction with a numeral, indicates the time within a twelve-hour period (midnight to noon or noon to midnight), specifically the time when the hour hand of a clock points precisely to the symbol or marking corresponding to the designated numeral.

odd.example: So let's see. There are two evens here and three odds.

off.meaning: (usually in phrases such as 'from the off', 'at the off', etc.) Beginning; starting point.
off.example: He has been very obviously an untrustworthy narrator right from the off.

offend.meaning: To hurt the feelings of; to displease; to make angry; to insult.

offender.meaning: One who gives or causes offense, or does something wrong.

offensive.example: The Marines today launched a major offensive.

offer.meaning: A proposal that has been made.
offer.example: I decline your offer to contract.

office.meaning: A ceremonial duty or service, particularly:

officer.meaning: One who has a position of authority in a hierarchical organization, especially in military, police or government organizations.

official.meaning: An office holder invested with powers and authorities.
official.example: David Barnes was the official charged with the running of the sports club.

officially.meaning: In an official manner; according to official rules or regulations.

offshore.meaning: An area or or portion of sea away from the shore.

oily.meaning: A marble with an oily lustre.

ointment.meaning: A viscous preparation of oils and/or fats, usually containing medication, used as a treatment or as an emollient.

old.meaning: (with the, invariable plural only) People who are old; old beings; the older generation, taken as a group.
old.example: A civilised society should always look after the old in the community.

old-fashioned.meaning: A cocktail made by muddling sugar with bitters and adding whiskey or, less commonly, brandy, served with a twist of citrus rind.

olive.meaning: A tree, Olea europaea, cultivated since ancient times in the Mediterranean for its fruit and the oil obtained from it.

olive oil.meaning: A vegetable oil, pressed from olives, and used in cooking and as a salad dressing; it is high in unsaturated fatty acids.

olympiad.meaning: A period of four years, by which the ancient Greeks reckoned time, being the interval from one celebration of the Olympic games to another, beginning with the victory of Corbus in the foot race, which took place in the year 776 BC; as, the era of the olympiads.

once.example: I have only once eaten pizza.

oneself.meaning: A person's self: general form of himself, herself, themself or yourself.
oneself.example: Teaching oneself to swim can be dangerous.

onion.meaning: A monocotyledonous plant (Allium cepa), allied to garlic, used as vegetable and spice.

online.meaning: To bring (a system, etc.) online; to promote to an active or running state.

onstage.meaning: On the part of a stage that is visible to the audience.

opening.meaning: To make something accessible or allow for passage by moving from a shut position.
opening.example: Turn the doorknob to open the door.

openly.meaning: In an open manner, visibly, not covertly.

opera.meaning: A theatrical work, combining drama, music, song and sometimes dance.

operate.meaning: To perform a work or labour; to exert power or strength, physical or mechanical; to act.

operation.meaning: The method by which a device performs its function.

opinion.meaning: A subjective belief, judgment or perspective that a person has formed about a topic, issue, person or thing.
opinion.example: Every man is a fool in some man's opinion.

opponent.meaning: One who opposes another; one who works or takes a position against someone or something; one who attempts to stop the progress of someone or something.
opponent.example: During the crackdown, many opponents of the regime were arrested.

opportunity.meaning: A chance for advancement, progress or profit.
opportunity.example: The world is full of opportunities and it's up to me to see them and pursue them.

oppose.meaning: To attempt to stop the progression of; to resist or antagonize by physical means, or by arguments, etc.; to contend against.
oppose.example: There is still time to oppose this plan.

opposite.meaning: Something opposite or contrary to something else.

opposition.meaning: The action of opposing or of being in conflict.

oppress.meaning: To keep down by unjust force.
oppress.example: The rural poor were oppressed by the land-owners.

oppression.meaning: The exercise of authority or power in a burdensome, cruel, or unjust manner.

optimism.meaning: A tendency to expect the best, or at least, a favourable outcome
optimism.example: I love her youth, her beauty and above all her optimism that everything will turn out fine.

optimist.meaning: A person who expects a favourable outcome

optimistic.meaning: Expecting the best in all possible ways.

option.meaning: One of a set of choices that can be made.

optional.meaning: Something that is not compulsory, especially part of an academic course.

or.meaning: Connects at least two alternative words, phrases, clauses, sentences, etc. each of which could make a passage true. In English, this is the "inclusive or." The "exclusive or" is formed by "either [...] or".
or.example: He might get cancer, or be hit by a bus, or God knows what.

oral.meaning: A spoken test or examination, particularly in a language class.
oral.example: We've got our Spanish oral tomorrow.

original.meaning: An object or other creation (e.g. narrative work) from which all later copies and variations are derived

originality.meaning: The quality of being original or novel.

originally.meaning: As it was in the beginning.
originally.example: Originally, this paper was white, but over the years it has yellowed with age.

originate.meaning: To cause to be, to bring into existence; to produce, initiate.

ornament.meaning: An element of decoration; that which embellishes or adorns.

orphan.meaning: A person, especially a minor, both or (rarely) one of whose parents have died.

other.meaning: An other, another (person, etc), more often rendered as another.
other.example: I'm afraid little Robbie does not always play well with others.

otherwise.example: He said he didn’t do it, but the evidence was otherwise.

ounce.meaning: An avoirdupois ounce, weighing 1/16 of an avoirdupois pound, or 28.3495 grams.

ours.meaning: That which belongs to us; the possessive case of we, used without a following noun.

ourselves.meaning: (reflexive pronoun) Us; the group including the speaker as the object of a verb or preposition when that group also is the subject.
ourselves.example: We should keep this for ourselves.

out.meaning: A means of exit, escape, reprieve, etc.
out.example: They wrote the law to give those organizations an out.

out of.meaning: Expressing motion away, literal or figurative; opposed to into.

outback.meaning: The most remote and desolate areas of Australia; the desert and areas too arid for growing crops.

outbreak.meaning: An eruption; the sudden appearance of a rash, disease, etc.
outbreak.example: Any epidemic outbreak causes understandable panic.

outcome.meaning: That which is produced or occurs as a result of an event or process.
outcome.example: A quality automobile is the outcome of the work of skilled engineers and thousands of workers.

outdistance.meaning: To run further or faster than another, or to finish a race with a large margin.

outdo.meaning: To excel; go beyond in performance; surpass.

outdoor.meaning: (in some African communities) To publicly display a child after it has been named

outdoors.meaning: (often preceded by "the") The environment outside of enclosed structures.

outfit.example: She wore a fashionable outfit with matching purse and shoes.

outgrow.meaning: To become too big in size or too mature in age or outlook to continue to want, need, use, experience, or accept some object, practice, condition, belief, etc.
outgrow.example: I used to have allergies but I outgrew all of them.

outlet.meaning: A vent or similar passage to allow the escape of something.

outline.meaning: A line marking the boundary of an object figure.

outlive.meaning: To live longer than; continue to live after the death of; overlive; survive.

outlook.meaning: A place from which something can be viewed.
outlook.example: Perched on the edge of the cliff was a hidden outlook.

out-of-date.meaning: Alternative form of out of date

outpatient.meaning: A patient who receives treatment at a hospital or clinic but is not admitted overnight; a receiver of ambulatory care.

output.meaning: Production; quantity produced, created, or completed.
output.example: The factory increased its output this year.

outrage.meaning: An excessively violent or vicious attack; an atrocity.

outrageous.meaning: Violating morality or decency; provoking indignation or affront.

outshine.meaning: To shine brighter than something else

overlap.meaning: Something that overlaps or is overlapped

overlook.meaning: A vista or point that gives a beautiful view.

overly.meaning: Superficial; not thorough; careless, negligent, inattentive.

overnight.example: Have you looked at the overnights yet?

overseas.example: Overseas branches of the company are doing well.

overshadow.meaning: To obscure something by casting a shadow.

oversize.meaning: The increased size of the bore of an engine when it is rebored.

overstep.meaning: A gait in which the hind foot touches ground in front of where the front foot touches the ground.

overtake.meaning: To pass a more slowly moving object or entity.
overtake.example: The car was so slow we were overtaken by a bus.

overthrow.meaning: A removal, especially of a ruler or government, by force or threat of force.

overtime.meaning: Working time outside of one's regular hours.
overtime.example: Workers are usually paid extra for working overtime.

overturn.meaning: A turning over or upside-down; inversion.

overwhelm.meaning: The state or condition of being overwhelmed.

overwhelming.meaning: To engulf, surge over and submerge.
overwhelming.example: The dinghy was overwhelmed by the great wave.

ow.meaning: An expression of one's own physical pain.
ow.example: Ouch! You stepped on my toe! That hurt!

owe.meaning: To be under an obligation to give something back to someone or to perform some action for someone.

owing.meaning: To be under an obligation to give something back to someone or to perform some action for someone.

owing to.example: I gave up my job as a typist owing to repetitive strain injury.

owl.meaning: Any of various birds of prey of the order Strigiformes that are primarily nocturnal and have forward-looking, binocular vision, limited eye movement, and good hearing.

own.meaning: Belonging to; possessed; proper to. Often marks a possessive determiner as reflexive, referring back to the subject of the clause or sentence.

owner.example: The police recovered the stolen car and returned it to its owner.

ox.meaning: An adult castrated male of cattle (B. taurus).

oxygen.meaning: The chemical element (symbol O) with an atomic number of 8 and relative atomic mass of 15.9994. It is a colorless and odorless gas.

ozone.meaning: An allotrope of oxygen (symbol O₃) having three atoms in the molecule instead of the usual two; it is a blue gas, generated from oxygen by electrical discharge.

palace.meaning: Official residence of a head of state or other dignitary, especially in a monarchical or imperial governmental system.

pallet.meaning: A portable platform, usually designed to be easily moved by a forklift, on which goods can be stacked, for transport or storage.

palm.meaning: Any of various evergreen trees from the family Palmae or Arecaceae, which are mainly found in the tropics.

pan.meaning: A wide, flat receptacle used around the house, especially for cooking.

pancake.meaning: A thin batter cake fried in a pan or on a griddle in oil or butter.

pandemic.meaning: A pandemic disease; a disease that affects a wide geographical area and a large proportion of the population.

panel.meaning: A (usually) rectangular section of a surface, or of a covering or of a wall, fence etc.
panel.example: Behind the picture was a panel on the wall.

panic.meaning: Overpowering fright, often affecting groups of people or animals.

pants.meaning: (Manchester) An outer garment that covers the body from the waist downwards, covering each leg separately, usually as far as the ankles; trousers.

papaya.meaning: A tropical American evergreen tree, Carica papaya, having large, yellow, edible fruit

paper.meaning: A sheet material used for writing on or printing on (or as a non-waterproof container), usually made by draining cellulose fibres from a suspension in water.

paperless.example: The paperless walls of the bedroom looked grey and cheerless.

parachute.meaning: A device, generally constructed from fabric, that is designed to employ air resistance to control the fall of an object.

parade.meaning: An organized procession consisting of a series of consecutive displays, performances, exhibits, etc. displayed by moving down a street past a crowd of spectators.
parade.example: The floats and horses in the parade were impressive, but the marching bands were really amazing.

paradise.meaning: The place where sanctified souls are believed to live after death.
paradise.example: Living in paradise comes with a price.

paradox.meaning: An apparently self-contradictory statement, which can only be true if it is false, and vice versa.
paradox.example: "This sentence is false" is a paradox.

paragraph.meaning: A passage in text that is about a different subject from the preceding text, marked by commencing on a new line, the first line sometimes being indented.

paralysis.meaning: The complete loss of voluntary control of part of a person's body, such as one or more limbs.

paramedic.meaning: An individual trained to medically stabilize people through various interventions, victims of trauma or medical events outside of a hospital setting and preparing them for transport to a medical facility.

paratrooper.meaning: A type of soldier who is trained to enter combat zones by parachuting from aircraft.

parcel.example: I saw a brown paper parcel on my doorstep.

parent.meaning: One of the two persons from whom one is immediately biologically descended; a mother or father.

parental.meaning: A person fulfilling a parental role.
parental.example: Nowadays there are all kinds of potential parentals besides parents, grandparents, aunts and uncles, step-parents, in-laws, older siblings and cousins, and those in civil unions.

park.meaning: An area of land set aside for environment preservation or recreation.

parking.meaning: To bring (something such as a vehicle) to a halt or store in a specified place.
parking.example: I parked the drive heads of my hard disk before travelling with my laptop.

parliament.meaning: A formal council summoned (especially by a monarch) to discuss important issues.

parrot.meaning: A kind of bird, many species of which are colourful and able to mimic human speech, of the order Psittaciformes or (narrowly) of the family Psittacidae.
parrot.example: I bought a wonderful parrot at the pet store.

partial.meaning: A partial derivative: a derivative with respect to one independent variable of a function in multiple variables while holding the other variables constant.

participant.example: All participants must adhere to the rules of the competition.

participate.meaning: To join in, to take part, to involve oneself (in something).

participation.meaning: The act of participating, of taking part in something.

participle.meaning: (grammar) A form of a verb that may function as an adjective or noun. English has two types of participles: the present participle and the past participle. In other languages, there are others, such as future, perfect, and future perfect participles.

particle.meaning: A very small piece of matter, a fragment; especially, the smallest possible part of something.

particular.meaning: A small individual part of something larger; a detail, a point.

partisan.meaning: An adherent to a party or faction.

partly.meaning: In part, or to some degree, but not completely.
partly.example: they partly finished the house so they could move in before winter;  the car was partly visible in the garage

partner.meaning: Someone who is associated with another in a common activity or interest.

partnership.meaning: The state of being associated with a partner.

part-time.meaning: For, during, or involving less than the normal time for some activity, especially the number of hours an employee works.

party.meaning: A person or group of people constituting a particular side in a contract or legal action.
party.example: The contract requires that the party of the first part pay the fee.

passage.meaning: A paragraph or section of text or music with particular meaning.
passage.example: She struggled to play the difficult passages.

passenger.meaning: One who rides or travels in a vehicle, but who does not operate it and is not a member of the crew.
passenger.example: Somebody in a team who does not do their fair share of the work.

passion.meaning: Any great, strong, powerful emotion, especially romantic love or extreme hate.
passion.example: We share a passion for books.

passport.meaning: An official document normally used for international journeys, which proves the identity and nationality of the person for whom it was issued.
passport.example: You will have to bring your passport to prove who you are.

password.meaning: A word used to gain admittance or to gain access to information; watchword.

pasta.meaning: Dough made from wheat and water and sometimes mixed with egg and formed into various shapes; often sold in dried form and typically boiled for eating.

pay.meaning: Money given in return for work; salary or wages.
pay.example: Many employers have rules designed to keep employees from comparing their pays.

pc.meaning: A percentage, a proportion (especially per hundred).
pc.example: only a small percent attain the top ranks

pea.meaning: A plant, Pisum sativum, member of the legume (Fabaceae) family.

peace.meaning: A state of tranquility, quiet, and harmony; absence of violence. For instance, a state free from civil disturbance.
peace.example: Our lounge strives to maintain an environment of peace for the comfort of our customers.

peaceful.meaning: Not at war or disturbed by strife or turmoil.

peach.meaning: A tree (Prunus persica), native to China and now widely cultivated throughout temperate regions, having pink flowers and edible fruit.

peak.meaning: A point; the sharp end or top of anything that terminates in a point; as, the peak, or front, of a cap.

peanut.meaning: A legume resembling a nut, the fruit of the plant Arachis hypogaea.

pear.meaning: An edible fruit produced by the pear tree, similar to an apple but elongated towards the stem.

pearl.meaning: A shelly concretion, usually rounded, and having a brilliant luster, with varying tints, found in the mantle, or between the mantle and shell, of certain bivalve mollusks, especially in the pearl oysters and river mussels, and sometimes in certain univalves. It is usually due to a secretion of shelly substance around some irritating foreign particle. Its substance is the same as nacre, or mother-of-pearl. Round lustrous pearls are used in jewellery.

pebble.meaning: A small stone, especially one rounded by the action of water.

peculiar.meaning: That which is peculiar; a sole or exclusive property; a prerogative; a characteristic.

pedal.meaning: A lever operated by one's foot that is used to control or power a machine or mechanism, such as a bicycle or piano
pedal.example: A piano usually has two or three pedals.

pedantic.meaning: Like a pedant, overly concerned with formal rules and trivial points of learning.

pedestrian.meaning: A walker; one who walks or goes on foot, especially as opposed to one who uses a vehicle.

peel.meaning: (usually uncountable) The skin or outer layer of a fruit, vegetable, etc.

peep.meaning: A quiet sound, particularly one from a baby bird.

peg.meaning: A cylindrical wooden or metal object used to fasten or as a bearing between objects.

pen.meaning: An enclosure (enclosed area) used to contain domesticated animals, especially sheep or cattle.
pen.example: There are two steers in the third pen.

penalty.example: The penalty for his crime was to do hard labor.

pence.meaning: In the United Kingdom and Ireland, a copper coin worth 1/240 of a pound sterling or Irish pound before decimalisation. Abbreviation: d.

penetrate.meaning: To enter into; to make way into the interior of; to pierce.

penguin.meaning: Any of several flightless sea birds, of order Sphenisciformes, found in the Southern Hemisphere, marked by their usual upright stance, walking on short legs, and (generally) their stark black and white plumage.

penicillin.meaning: Any of a group of narrow-spectrum antibiotics obtained from Penicillium molds or synthesized; they have a beta-lactam structure; most are active against gram-positive bacteria and used in the treatment of various infections and diseases.

penniless.meaning: Lacking even the smallest amount of money.

penny.meaning: In the United Kingdom and Ireland, a copper coin worth 1/240 of a pound sterling or Irish pound before decimalisation. Abbreviation: d.

pension.meaning: An annuity paid regularly as benefit due to a retired employee, serviceman etc. in consideration of past services, originally and chiefly by a government but also by various private pension schemes.
pension.example: Many old people depend on their pension to pay the bills.

pentagon.meaning: A polygon with five sides and five angles.

people.meaning: Used as plural of person; a body of human beings considered generally or collectively; a group of two or more persons.
people.example: There were so many people at the restaurant last night.

pepper.meaning: A plant of the family Piperaceae.

permit.meaning: An artifact or document rendering something allowed or legal.
permit.example: A construction permit can be obtained from the town offices.

perseverance.meaning: Continuing in a course of action without regard to discouragement, opposition or previous failure.

persist.meaning: To go on stubbornly or resolutely.

persistence.example: You've got to admire his persistence. He's asked her out every day for a month even though she keeps turning him down.

persistent.meaning: Obstinately refusing to give up or let go.
persistent.example: She has had a persistent cough for weeks.

person.meaning: An individual; usually a human being.
person.example: Each person is unique, both mentally and physically.

personal.meaning: An advertisement by which individuals attempt to meet others with similar interests.

personality.meaning: A set of non-physical psychological and social qualities that make a person (or thing) distinct from another.
personality.example: The president has a unique personality.

personification.meaning: A person, thing or name typifying a certain quality or idea; an embodiment or exemplification.
personification.example: Adolf Hitler was the personification of anti-Semitism.

personify.meaning: To be an example of; to have all the attributes of.
personify.example: Mozart could be said to personify musical genius.

perspiration.meaning: The action or process of perspiring.

persuade.meaning: To successfully convince (someone) to agree to, accept, or do something, usually through reasoning and verbal influence.
persuade.example: That salesman was able to persuade me into buying this bottle of lotion.

persuasion.meaning: The act of persuading, or trying to do so; the addressing of arguments to someone with the intention of changing their mind or convincing them of a certain point of view, course of action etc.

pessimist.meaning: Someone who habitually expects the worst outcome; one who looks on the dark side of things.

pessimistic.meaning: Marked by pessimism and little hopefulness; expecting the worst.
pessimistic.example: a pessimistic view of the future

pet.meaning: An animal kept as a companion.

petrol.meaning: Petroleum, a fluid consisting of a mixture of refined petroleum hydrocarbons, primarily consisting of octane, commonly used as a motor fuel.

petrol station.meaning: A filling station, gas station; a facility selling fuel for road motor vehicles

petty.meaning: (usually in the plural) A little schoolboy, either in grade or size.

ph.meaning: In the way it sounds, particularly: written to describe the sound rather than the dictionary spelling.
ph.example: The hard words in the passage have been spelled phonetically.

pharmacist.meaning: A professional who dispenses prescription drugs in a hospital or retail pharmacy.

pharmacy.meaning: (countable) A place where prescription drugs are dispensed; a dispensary.

phenomenon.meaning: A thing or being, event or process, perceptible through senses; or a fact or occurrence thereof.

phoenix.meaning: A mythological bird, said to be the only one of its kind, which lives for 500 years and then dies by burning to ashes on a pyre of its own making, ignited by the sun. It then arises anew from the ashes.

phone.meaning: A device for transmitting conversations and other sounds in real time across distances, now often a small portable unit also capable of running software etc.

pie.meaning: A type of pastry that consists of an outer crust and a filling.
pie.example: The family had steak and kidney pie for dinner and cherry pie for dessert.

piece.meaning: A part of a larger whole, usually in such a form that it is able to be separated from other parts.
piece.example: I’d like another piece of pie.

piety.example: Colleen's piety led her to make sacrifices that most people would not have made.

pig.meaning: Any of several intelligent mammalian species of the genus Sus, having cloven hooves, bristles and a nose adapted for digging; especially the domesticated animal Sus scrofa.
pig.example: The man kept a pen with two pigs that he fed from carrots to cabbage.

pile.meaning: A mass of things heaped together; a heap.

pilgrim.meaning: One who travels, especially on a journey to visit sites of religious significance.

pill.meaning: A small, usually round or cylindrical object designed for easy swallowing, usually containing some sort of medication.

pillow.meaning: A soft cushion used to support the head in bed.

pillowcase.meaning: A washable, easily removable cloth cover for pillows.

pilot.meaning: A person who steers a ship, a helmsman.

pin.meaning: A needle without an eye (usually) made of drawn-out steel wire with one end sharpened and the other flattened or rounded into a head, used for fastening.

pine.meaning: Any coniferous tree of the genus Pinus.
pine.example: The northern slopes were covered mainly in pine.

pineapple.meaning: A tropical plant, Ananas comosus, native to South America, having thirty or more long, spined and pointed leaves surrounding a thick stem.

pint.meaning: A unit of volume, equivalent to:

pipe.meaning: Meanings relating to a wind instrument.

piracy.meaning: Robbery at sea, a violation of international law; taking a ship away from the control of those who are legally entitled to it.
piracy.example: How should the international community respond to Somali piracy?

pirate.meaning: A criminal who plunders at sea; commonly attacking merchant vessels, though often pillaging port towns.
pirate.example: You should be cautious due to the Somali pirates.
