pit.example: The meadow around the town is full of old pits.

pitch.meaning: A sticky, gummy substance secreted by trees; sap.
pitch.example: It is hard to get this pitch off my hand.

pity.meaning: A feeling of sympathy at the misfortune or suffering of someone or something.
pity.example: I can't feel any pity towards the gang, who got injured while attempting to break into a flat.

pizza.meaning: A baked Italian dish of a thinly rolled bread dough crust typically topped before baking with tomato sauce, cheese and other ingredients such as meat, vegetables or fruit
pizza.example: Want to go out for pizza tonight?

place.meaning: (physical) An area; somewhere within an area.

plague.meaning: (often used with the, sometimes capitalized: the Plague) The bubonic plague, the pestilent disease caused by the virulent bacterium Yersinia pestis.

plan.meaning: A drawing showing technical details of a building, machine, etc., with unwanted details omitted, and often using symbols rather than detailed drawing to represent doors, valves, etc.
plan.example: The plans for many important buildings were once publicly available.

planet.meaning: Each of the seven major bodies which move relative to the fixed stars in the night sky—the Moon, Mercury, Venus, the Sun, Mars, Jupiter and Saturn.

planning.example: The architect planned the building for the client.

plant.meaning: An organism that is not an animal, especially an organism capable of photosynthesis. Typically a small or herbaceous organism of this kind, rather than a tree.
plant.example: The garden had a couple of trees, and a cluster of colourful plants around the border.

plastic.meaning: A synthetic, solid, hydrocarbon-based polymer, whether thermoplastic or thermosetting.

plate.meaning: A slightly curved but almost flat dish from which food is served or eaten.
plate.example: I filled my plate from the bountiful table.

platform.meaning: A raised stage from which speeches are made and on which musical and other performances are made.

play.meaning: Activity for amusement only, especially among the young.

pneumonia.meaning: An acute or chronic inflammation of the lungs caused by viruses, bacteria or other microorganisms, or sometimes by physical or chemical irritants.

pocket.meaning: A bag stitched to an item of clothing, used for carrying small items.

pocket money.meaning: A small sum of money given to a child, by a parent or guardian.

poem.meaning: A literary piece written in verse.

poetry.meaning: Literature composed in verse or language exhibiting conscious attention to patterns and rhythm.

point of view.meaning: A position from which something is seen; outlook; standpoint.
point of view.example: From an economist's point of view, business is all about money.

pointless.meaning: Having no point or sharp tip; terminating squarely or in a rounded end.

poison.meaning: A substance that is harmful or lethal to a living organism.
poison.example: We used a poison to kill the weeds.

poisonous.meaning: Containing sufficient poison to be dangerous to touch or ingest.

polar bear.meaning: A very large bear, Ursus maritimus found in the Arctic Circle, white in appearance and very furry.

pole.meaning: Originally, a stick; now specifically, a long and slender piece of metal or (especially) wood, used for various construction or support purposes.

police.meaning: A civil force granted the legal authority for law enforcement and maintaining public order.

police officer.meaning: A peace officer and member of a police force, i.e. policeman or policewoman.

police station.meaning: A building serving as the headquarters of a branch of the police force, and sometimes as a temporary place of confinement for offenders.

policy.meaning: A principle of behaviour, conduct etc. thought to be desirable or necessary, especially as formally expressed by a government or other authoritative body.
policy.example: The Communist Party has a policy of returning power to the workers.

polish.example: A good silver polish will remove tarnish easily.

polite.meaning: To polish; to refine; to render polite.

politely.example: If pressed about a serious accusation like rape, you can politely reply that you can’t answer questions pertaining to such an allegation without legal representation and wish to remain silent. ― G.S. Luthra, New Jersey Beach Beat Down Shows Why It’s Foolish To Resist Police

politician.meaning: One engaged in politics, especially an elected or appointed government official.
politician.example: Politicians should serve the country's interest.

port.meaning: A place on the coast at which ships can shelter, or dock to load and unload cargo or passengers.

portrait.meaning: A painting or other picture of a person, especially the head and shoulders.

positive.meaning: A thing capable of being affirmed; something real or actual.

possess.meaning: To have; to have ownership of.
possess.example: He does not even possess a working telephone.

possessed.meaning: To have; to have ownership of.
possessed.example: He does not even possess a working telephone.

possession.meaning: Control or occupancy of something for which one does not necessarily have private property rights.

possibly.meaning: (modifying a clause or predicate) Perhaps; indicates that the proposition may be true (is not certainly false) regardless of any facts or circumstances known to, stated by or implied by the speaker.
possibly.example: It was possibly the costliest mistake in the organization's history.

post.meaning: A long dowel or plank protruding from the ground; a fencepost; a lightpost.
post.example: ram a post into the ground

post office.meaning: A place (building, office, shop, or counter) concerned with the business of delivering letters, post or mail and selling stamps, etc.

postal.meaning: Relating to the collection, sorting and delivery of mail.

postcard.meaning: A rectangular piece of thick paper or thin cardboard intended to be written on and mailed without an envelope. In the case of a picture postcard one side carries a picture or photograph.

poster.meaning: A picture of a celebrity, an event etc., intended to be attached to a wall.
poster.example: He has posters of his favorite band, sports teams and holiday resorts up.

postman.meaning: Someone (implied male) who delivers the post (mail) to, and/or collects the post from, residential or commercial addresses, or from public mailboxes.

postpone.meaning: To delay or put off an event, appointment etc.

pot.meaning: A flat-bottomed vessel (usually metal) used for cooking food.

potato.meaning: The tuber of a plant, Solanum tuberosum, eaten as a starchy vegetable, particularly in the Americas and Europe; this plant.

potent.meaning: A heraldic fur formed by a regular tessellation of blue and white T shapes.

prayer.meaning: A practice of communicating with one's God.
prayer.example: Through prayer I ask for God's blessings.

precede.meaning: Brief editorial preface (usually to an article or essay)

precious.meaning: Someone (or something) who is loved; a darling.

precise.meaning: (NNES or European Union documents) To make or render precise; to specify.

precisely.example: I always try to express myself precisely.

predicament.meaning: A definite class, state or condition.

predicate.meaning: (grammar) The part of the sentence (or clause) which states something about the subject or the object of the sentence.
predicate.example: In "The dog barked very loudly", the subject is "the dog" and the predicate is "barked very loudly".

predicative.meaning: (grammar) An element of the predicate of a sentence which supplements the subject or object by means of the verb. Predicatives may be nominal or adjectival.

predictable.example: a boring film with a predictable ending

prediction.meaning: A statement of what will happen in the future.

predictive.example: The amount of rain in April is predictive of the number of mosquitoes in May.

predictor.meaning: Something that anticipates, predicts or foretells.
predictor.example: The predictor in the traffic-light control circuit tries to figure out how fast to change the lights.

prefect.meaning: An official of Ancient Rome who controlled or superintended a particular command, charge, department, etc.
prefect.example: the prefect of the aqueducts; the prefect of a camp, of a fleet, of the city guard, or of provisions; the pretorian prefect, who was commander of the troops guarding the emperor's person

prefer.meaning: To be in the habit of choosing something rather than something else; to favor; to like better.

preferable.meaning: Better than some other option; preferred.

preferably.meaning: In preference; by choice; in a preferable manner.

preference.meaning: The selection of one thing or person over others (with the main adposition being "for" in relation to the thing or person, but possibly also "of")
preference.example: He has a preference for crisp wines.

prehistoric.meaning: Having lasted from a remote period; having been of long duration; of great age, very old.
prehistoric.example: an ancient city  an ancient forest

prehuman.meaning: One of the human-like creatures prior to Homo sapiens.

prejudge.meaning: To form a judgment of (something) in advance.

prejudice.meaning: An adverse judgment or opinion formed beforehand or without knowledge of the facts.

pressure.meaning: A pressing; a force applied to a surface.
pressure.example: Apply pressure to the wound to stop the bleeding.

prestige.meaning: The quality of how good the reputation of something or someone is, how favourably something or someone is regarded.
prestige.example: Oxford has a university of very high prestige.

prestigious.example: She has a prestigious job with an international organization.

presumably.example: Presumably, he will attend the opening.

pretend.meaning: To claim, to allege, especially when falsely or as a form of deliberate deception.

pretty.meaning: A pretty person; a term of address to a pretty person.

prevail.meaning: To be superior in strength, dominance, influence or frequency; to have or gain the advantage over others; to have the upper hand; to outnumber others.
prevail.example: Red colour prevails in the Canadian flag.

prevent.meaning: To stop (an outcome); to keep from (doing something).
prevent.example: I brush my teeth regularly to prevent them from turning yellow.

prevention.meaning: The act of preventing or hindering; obstruction of action, access, or approach; thwarting.

preventive.meaning: A thing that prevents, hinders, or acts as an obstacle to.

previous.meaning: An existing criminal record (short for "previous convictions")
previous.example: It turned out the shoplifter had a lot of previous.

previously.meaning: (with present-tense constructions) First; beforehand, in advance.

price.meaning: The cost required to gain possession of something.

priceless.meaning: So precious as not to be sold at any price; invaluable.

prick.meaning: A small hole or perforation, caused by piercing.

pride.meaning: The quality or state of being proud; an unreasonable overestimation of one's own superiority in terms of talents, looks, wealth, importance etc., which manifests itself in lofty airs, distance, reserve and often contempt of others.

priest.meaning: A religious clergyman (clergywoman, clergyperson) who is trained to perform services or sacrifices at a church or temple
priest.example: The Israelite priests were descended from Moses' brother Aaron.

primarily.meaning: (focus) Of a primary or central nature, first and foremost

primary.meaning: A primary election; a preliminary election to select a political candidate of a political party.

primary school.meaning: The first formal, obligatory school. Usually begins with nursery school or first grade and ends at fifth or sixth grade.
primary school.example: The child's mother was tearful as he boarded the bus for his first day of primary school.

prime.meaning: The first hour of daylight; the first canonical hour.

prime minister.meaning: In a parliamentary democracy, the chief member of the cabinet and head of the government; often the leader of the majority party.
prime minister.example: This is a list of all prime ministers since Churchill.

primitive.meaning: An original or primary word; a word not derived from another, as opposed to derivative.

prince.meaning: A (male) ruler, a sovereign; a king, monarch.

princess.meaning: A female member of a royal family other than a queen, especially a daughter or granddaughter.

procedure.meaning: A particular method for performing a task.

proceed.meaning: To move, pass, or go forward or onward; to advance; to carry on

process.meaning: A series of events which produce a result (the product).
process.example: This product of last month's quality standards committee is quite good, even though the process was flawed.

procrastination.meaning: The act of postponing, delaying or putting off, especially habitually or intentionally.

produce.meaning: To yield, make or manufacture; to generate.

producer.meaning: An individual or organization that creates goods and services.

product.example: That store offers a variety of products.  We've got to sell a lot of product by the end of the month.

production.meaning: The act of producing, making or creating something.
production.example: The widget making machine is being used for production now.

productive.meaning: Capable of producing something, especially in abundance; fertile.

profession.meaning: A declaration of belief, faith or one's opinion, whether genuine or pretended.
profession.example: Despite his continued professions of innocence, the court eventually sentenced him to five years.

professional.meaning: A person who belongs to a profession

professor.meaning: The most senior rank for an academic at a university or similar institution, informally also known as "full professor." Abbreviated Prof.

profile.meaning: The outermost shape, view, or edge of an object.
profile.example: His fingers traced the profile of the handle.

profit.meaning: Total income or cash flow minus expenditures. The money or other benefit a non-governmental organization or individual receives in exchange for products and services sold at an advertised price.

programmer.meaning: One who writes computer programs; a software developer.

programming.meaning: To enter a program or other instructions into (a computer or other electronic device) to instruct it to do a particular task.
programming.example: He programmed the DVR to record his favorite show.

progress.meaning: Movement or advancement through a series of events, or points in time; development through time.
progress.example: Testing for the new antidote is currently in progress.

progressive.meaning: A person who actively favors or strives for progress towards improved conditions, as in society or government.

prohibit.meaning: To forbid, disallow, or proscribe officially; to make illegal or illicit.
prohibit.example: The restaurant prohibits smoking on the patio.

prohibition.meaning: An act of prohibiting, forbidding, disallowing, or proscribing something.

project.meaning: A planned endeavor, usually with a specific goal and accomplished in several steps or stages.

projection.meaning: Something which projects, protrudes, juts out, sticks out, or stands out.
projection.example: The face of the cliff had many projections that were big enough for birds to nest on.

prominence.meaning: The state of being prominent: widely known or eminent.

prominent.meaning: Standing out, or projecting; jutting; protuberant

promise.meaning: An oath or affirmation; a vow
promise.example: if I make a promise, I always stick to it;  he broke his promise

promote.meaning: To raise (someone) to a more important, responsible, or remunerative job or rank.
promote.example: He promoted his clerk to office manager.

promotion.meaning: An advancement in rank or position.
promotion.example: I'll have to give myself a promotion!

promptly.meaning: In prompt manner; both soon and quickly.

protect.meaning: To keep safe; to defend; to guard; to prevent harm coming to.
protect.example: Condoms are designed to protect against sexually-transmitted diseases.

protection.meaning: The process of keeping (something or someone) safe.

protest.meaning: A formal objection, especially one by a group.
protest.example: They lodged a protest with the authorities.

proud.meaning: Feeling honoured (by something); feeling happy or satisfied about an event or fact; gratified.
proud.example: I am proud of Sivu’s schoolwork.

proverb.meaning: A phrase expressing a basic truth which may be applied to common situations.

provide.meaning: To make a living; earn money for necessities.
provide.example: It is difficult to provide for my family working on minimum wage.

provided.meaning: To make a living; earn money for necessities.
provided.example: It is difficult to provide for my family working on minimum wage.

province.meaning: A region of the earth or of a continent; a district or country.

provision.meaning: An item of goods or supplies, especially food, obtained for future use.

proximity.meaning: Closeness; the state of being near as in space, time, or relationship.
proximity.example: The proximity of the heat source allowed it to be detected by the sensor.

psychological.example: I'm concerned about their psychological well-being.

psychologically.example: The new novel is a psychologically complex thriller.

psychologist.meaning: An expert in the field of psychology.

psychology.meaning: The study of the human mind.

pub.meaning: A public house where beverages, primarily alcoholic, may be bought and consumed, also providing food and sometimes entertainment such as live music or television.

public.meaning: The people in general, regardless of membership of any particular group.
public.example: Members of the public may not proceed beyond this point.

public transport.meaning: Any form of transport that can be used by a member of public (who usually pays a fare); as opposed to private ownership of e.g. cars.

publication.meaning: The act of publishing printed or other matter.

publicity.meaning: Advertising or other activity designed to rouse public interest in something.

publicly.meaning: In public, openly, in an open and public manner.

publish.meaning: To issue (something, such as printed work) for distribution and/or sale.
publish.example: Most of the sketches Faulkner published in 1925 appeared in the Sunday magazine section of the New Orleans Times-Picayune.

pudding.meaning: Any of various dishes, sweet or savoury, prepared by boiling or steaming, or from batter.

pull.example: He gave the hair a sharp pull and it came out.

pullover.meaning: A sweater that must be put on by pulling it over the head; a sweater without buttons or a zipper in front

pulse.meaning: A normally regular beat felt when arteries are depressed, caused by the pumping action of the heart.

pump.meaning: A device for moving or compressing a liquid or gas.
pump.example: This pump can deliver 100 gallons of water per minute.

pumpkin.meaning: A domesticated plant, in species Cucurbita pepo, similar in growth pattern, foliage, flower, and fruit to the squash or melon.

punch.meaning: A hit or strike with one's fist.

punctuation.meaning: A set of symbols and marks which are used to clarify meaning in text by separating strings of words into clauses, phrases and sentences.

punish.meaning: To cause to suffer for crime or misconduct, to administer disciplinary action.
punish.example: If a prince violates the law, then he must be punished like an ordinary person.

punishment.meaning: The act or process of punishing, imposing and/or applying a sanction.

pupil.meaning: A learner under the supervision of a teacher or professor.

puppy.meaning: A young dog, especially before sexual maturity (12-18 months)

purchase.meaning: The acquisition of title to, or property in, anything for a price; buying for money or its equivalent.
purchase.example: They offer a free hamburger with the purchase of a drink.

pure.meaning: One who, or that which, is pure.

purify.meaning: To cleanse, or rid of impurities.

purple.meaning: A colour/color that is a dark blend of red and blue; dark magenta.

purpose.meaning: An objective to be reached; a target; an aim; a goal.

purse.meaning: A small bag for carrying money.

pursue.meaning: To follow urgently, originally with intent to capture or harm; to chase.

pursuit.example: Unremitting pursuit of wealth doesn't bring happiness, particularly if successful.

push.meaning: A short, directed application of force; an act of pushing.
push.example: Give the door a hard push if it sticks.

put.meaning: A right to sell something at a predetermined price.

puzzle.meaning: Anything that is difficult to understand or make sense of.
puzzle.example: Where he went after he left the house is a puzzle.

quake.example: We felt a quake in the apartment every time the train went by.

qualification.meaning: The act or process of qualifying for a position, achievement etc.
qualification.example: Qualification for this organization is extraordinarily difficult.

qualified.meaning: Meeting the standards, requirements, and training for a position.

qualify.meaning: An instance of throwing and catching each prop at least twice.

quality.example: Quality of life is usually determined by health, education, and income.

quantity.meaning: A fundamental, generic term used when referring to the measurement (count, amount) of a scalar, vector, number of items or to some other way of denominating the value of a collection or group of items.
quantity.example: You have to choose between quantity and quality.

quarantine.meaning: The desert in which Christ fasted for 40 days according to the Bible.

quarrel.meaning: A verbal dispute or heated argument.
quarrel.example: We got into a silly quarrel about what food to order.

quarrelsome.meaning: Argumentative; fond of or prone to quarreling.
quarrelsome.example: She's too quarrelsome to participate in a civil conversation.

queen.meaning: A female monarch. Example: Queen Victoria.

racial.meaning: A skill possessed by all characters of a certain race.

racism.meaning: Belief that there are distinct human races with inherent differences which determine their abilities, and generally that some are superior and others inferior.

racist.meaning: A person who believes in or supports racism; a person who believes that a particular race is superior to others.

rack.meaning: A series of one or more shelves, stacked one above the other

racket.meaning: A racquet: an implement with a handle connected to a round frame strung with wire, sinew, or plastic cords, and used to hit a ball, such as in tennis or a birdie in badminton.

radar.meaning: A method of detecting distant objects and determining their position, velocity, or other characteristics by analysis of sent radio waves (usually microwaves) reflected from their surfaces

radiation.meaning: The shooting forth of anything from a point or surface, like diverging rays of light.

radical.meaning: (historical: 19th-century Britain) A member of the most progressive wing of the Liberal Party; someone favouring social reform (but generally stopping short of socialism).

radically.meaning: In a radical manner; fundamentally; very.

radio.meaning: The technology that allows for the transmission of sound or other signals by modulation of electromagnetic waves.

radium.meaning: The chemical element (symbol Ra) with an atomic number of 88. It is a soft, shiny and silvery radioactive alkaline earth metal.

rafter.meaning: One of a series of sloped beams that extend from the ridge or hip to the downslope perimeter or eave, designed to support the roof deck and its associated loads.

rail.meaning: A horizontal bar extending between supports and used for support or as a barrier; a railing.

railroad.meaning: A permanent road consisting of fixed metal rails to drive trains or similar motorized vehicles on.
railroad.example: Many railroads roughly follow the trace of older land - and/or water roads

railway.meaning: A transport system using rails used to move passengers or goods.

rain.meaning: Condensed water falling from a cloud.
rain.example: The rains came late that year.

rainbow.meaning: A multicoloured arch in the sky, produced by prismatic refraction of light within droplets of rain in the air.

raincoat.meaning: A waterproof coat to be worn in the rain.

rainfall.meaning: The amount of rain that falls on a single occasion

rainforest.meaning: A forest in a climate with high annual rainfall and no dry season.

rainstorm.meaning: A storm characterized by substantial, heavy rainfall.

rainy.example: Due to the rainy weather, we decided not to play in the park.

raise.meaning: An increase in wages or salary; a rise (UK).
raise.example: The boss gave me a raise.

rally.meaning: A public gathering or mass meeting that is not mainly a protest and is organized to inspire enthusiasm for a cause.

ramp.meaning: An inclined surface that connects two levels; an incline.

range.meaning: A line or series of mountains, buildings, etc.

rank.meaning: Strong of its kind or in character; unmitigated; virulent; thorough; utter (used of negative things).

rap.meaning: A sharp blow with something hard.
rap.example: The teacher gave the wayward pupil a rap across the knuckles with her ruler.

rapid.meaning: (often in the plural) a rough section of a river or stream which is difficult to navigate due to the swift and turbulent motion of the water.

rapidly.meaning: With speed; in a rapid manner.
rapidly.example: She packed her case rapidly and hurried out.

rarely.meaning: Not occurring at a regular interval; seldom; not often.
rarely.example: Rarely do you ever find an eagle this far up the river.

rash.meaning: Acting too quickly without considering the risks and consequences; not careful; hasty.
rash.example: rash words spoken in the heat of debate

reading.meaning: To look at and interpret letters or other information that is written.

real estate.meaning: Property that cannot easily be moved, usually buildings and the ground they are built on.

realistic.meaning: Expressed or represented as being accurate, practicable, or not idealistic.
realistic.example: A realistic appraisal of the situation.

reality.meaning: The state of being actual or real.
reality.example: The reality of the crash scene on TV dawned upon him only when he saw the victim was no actor but his friend.

really.meaning: In a way or manner that is real, not unreal.

rear.meaning: To bring up to maturity, as offspring; to educate; to instruct; to foster.

rearrange.meaning: To change the order or arrangement of (one or more items).

reasonable.meaning: Having the faculty of reason; rational, reasoning.

reasonably.example: They were able handle their disagreements reasonably.

rebel.meaning: A person who resists an established authority, often violently

rebuild.meaning: A process or result of rebuilding.

recall.meaning: The action or fact of calling someone or something back.

receipt.meaning: The act of receiving, or the fact of having been received.
receipt.example: A balance payable on receipt of the goods.

receive.meaning: An operation in which data is received.

recent.meaning: Having happened a short while ago.

receptionist.meaning: An employee (such as a secretary) who works in reception (receiving visitors and/or calls) for a person or business, especially an office.

recession.meaning: The act or an instance of receding or withdrawing.

rectangular.meaning: Having a shape like a rectangle.

recycled.meaning: To break down and reuse component materials.
recycled.example: Both paper and plastic can be recycled.

recycling.meaning: To break down and reuse component materials.
recycling.example: Both paper and plastic can be recycled.

red.meaning: Any of a range of colours having the longest wavelengths, 670 nm, of the visible spectrum; a primary additive colour for transmitted light: the colour obtained by subtracting green and blue from white light using magenta and yellow filters; the colour of blood, ripe strawberries, etc.

redo.meaning: A repeated action; a doing again, refurbishment, etc.

reduce.meaning: To bring down the size, quantity, quality, value or intensity of something; to diminish, to lower.
reduce.example: to reduce weight, speed, heat, expenses, price, personnel etc.

reduction.meaning: The act, process, or result of reducing.

reed.meaning: Any of various types of tall stiff perennial grass-like plants growing together in groups near water.

reef.meaning: A chain or range of rocks, sand, or coral lying at or near the surface of the water.

referee.meaning: An umpire or judge; an official who makes sure the rules are followed during a game.
referee.example: The referee kicked Jim out of the game for fighting.

referent.meaning: The specific entity in the world that a word or phrase identifies or denotes.

refinery.meaning: A building, or a mass of machinery, used to produce refined products such as sugar, oil, or metals.

reflect.meaning: To bend back (light, etc.) from a surface.
reflect.example: A mirror reflects the light that shines on it.

reflection.meaning: The act of reflecting or the state of being reflected.

reflective.meaning: That reflects, or redirects back to the source.

reform.meaning: The change of something that is defective, broken, inefficient or otherwise negative, in order to correct or improve it
reform.example: A major reform is needed to improve the efficiency in the factory.

refrain.meaning: To hold back, to restrain (someone or something).

refresh.meaning: The periodic energizing required to maintain the contents of computer memory, the display luminance of a computer screen, etc.

refreshments.meaning: The action of refreshing; a means of restoring strength, energy or vigour.

refrigerator.meaning: A household appliance used for keeping food fresh by refrigeration (short form fridge).

refuge.meaning: A state of safety, protection or shelter.

refugee.meaning: A person seeking refuge in a foreign country out of fear of political persecution or the prospect of such persecution in their home country, i.e., a person seeking political asylum.

refund.example: If the camera is faulty, you can return it to the store where you bought it for a full refund.

refuse.meaning: Collectively, items or material that have been discarded; rubbish, garbage.

refute.meaning: To prove (something) to be false or incorrect.

regain.meaning: To get back; to recover possession of.

rejoin.meaning: To join again; to unite after separation.

relate.meaning: To tell in a descriptive way.
relate.example: Please relate the circumstances of your journey here today.

related.meaning: To tell in a descriptive way.
related.example: Please relate the circumstances of your journey here today.

relation.meaning: The manner in which two things may be associated.
relation.example: The relation between diet and health is complex.

relationship.meaning: Connection or association; the condition of being related.

relative.meaning: Someone in the same family; someone connected by blood, marriage, or adoption.
relative.example: Why do my relatives always talk about sex?

relatively.meaning: Proportionally, in relation to some larger scale thing.
relatively.example: He measured his success relatively, that is, competitively.

relativity.meaning: The state of being relative to something else.

relaxation.meaning: The act of relaxing or the state of being relaxed; the opposite of stress or tension; the aim of recreation and leisure activities.

release.meaning: The event of setting (someone or something) free (e.g. hostages, slaves, prisoners, caged animals, hooked or stuck mechanisms).

relevant.meaning: Directly related, connected, or pertinent to a topic.
relevant.example: His mother provided some relevant background information concerning his medical condition.

reliable.meaning: Something or someone reliable or dependable

relic.meaning: That which remains; that which is left after loss or decay; a remaining portion.

relief.meaning: The removal of stress or discomfort.
relief.example: I sighed with relief when I found out that my daughter hadn't got lost, but was waiting for me at home.

relieve.meaning: To ease (a person, person's thoughts etc.) from mental distress; to stop (someone) feeling anxious or worried, to alleviate the distress of.
relieve.example: I was greatly relieved by the jury's verdict.

relieved.meaning: To ease (a person, person's thoughts etc.) from mental distress; to stop (someone) feeling anxious or worried, to alleviate the distress of.
relieved.example: I was greatly relieved by the jury's verdict.

religion.meaning: Belief in a spiritual or metaphysical reality (often including at least one deity), accompanied by practices or rituals pertaining to the belief.
religion.example: My brother tends to value religion, but my sister not as much.

religious.meaning: A member of a religious order, i.e. a monk or nun.

rely.meaning: (with on or upon, formerly also with in) to trust; to have confidence in; to depend.

remain.meaning: (chiefly in the plural) That which is left; relic; remainder.

remainder.meaning: A part or parts remaining after some has/have been removed.
remainder.example: My son ate part of his cake and I ate the remainder.

remaining.meaning: To stay behind while others withdraw; to be left after others have been removed or destroyed; to be left after a number or quantity has been subtracted or cut off; to be left as not included or comprised.

remains.meaning: (chiefly in the plural) That which is left; relic; remainder.

remark.meaning: An act of pointing out or noticing; notice or observation.

remarkable.meaning: Worthy of being remarked or noted; notable

remarkably.example: He performed the piece remarkably, offering novel interpretations to its nearly cliched passages.

remember.meaning: To recall from one's memory; to have an image in one's memory.

remembrance.meaning: The act of remembering; a holding in mind, or bringing to mind; recollection.

remind.meaning: To cause one to experience a memory (of someone or something); to bring to the notice or consideration (of a person).

reminder.example: He left a note as a reminder to get groceries.

remote.meaning: An element of broadcast programming originating away from the station's or show's control room.

remote control.meaning: A device used to operate an appliance (such as a television), vehicle or mechanical toy from a short distance away.

repress.meaning: A record pressed again; a repressing.

repression.meaning: The act of repressing; state of being repressed.
repression.example: History shows that when governments fear the truth and increase repression, their days are limited.

reprint.meaning: A book, pamphlet or other printed matter that has been published once before but is now being released again.
reprint.example: The reprint is much less expensive than a first edition.

reproduce.meaning: To produce an image or copy of.

republic.meaning: A state where sovereignty rests with the people or their representatives, rather than with a monarch or emperor; a country with no monarchy.
republic.example: The United States is a republic; the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland is a constitutional monarchy.

request.meaning: Act of requesting (with the adposition at in the presence of possessives, and on in their absence).

require.meaning: To ask (someone) for something; to request.

requirement.meaning: A necessity or prerequisite; something required or obligatory. Its adpositions are generally of in relation to who or what has given it, on in relation to whom or what it is given to, and for in relation to what is required.
requirement.example: There was a requirement of the government on citizens for paying taxes.

rescue.meaning: An act or episode of rescuing, saving.

research.meaning: Diligent inquiry or examination to seek or revise facts, principles, theories, applications, etc.; laborious or continued search after truth.
research.example: The research station that houses Wang and his team is outside Lijiang, a city of about 1.2 million people.

resemble.meaning: To be like or similar to (something); to represent as similar.

reservation.meaning: The act of reserving, withholding or keeping back.
reservation.example: The committee authorised the reservation of funds.

residence.meaning: The place where one lives; one's home.

resident.meaning: A person, animal or plant living at a certain location or in a certain area.
resident.example: The tiger lily is a resident of Asia.

residential.meaning: A trip during which people temporarily live together.
residential.example: The youth group organises annual residentials.

resign.meaning: To give up; to relinquish ownership of.

resistance.meaning: The act of resisting, or the capacity to resist.
resistance.example: the resistance of bacteria to certain antibiotics

result.meaning: That which results; the conclusion or end to which any course or condition of things leads, or which is obtained by any process or operation; consequence or effect.
result.example: the result of a course of action;  the result of a mathematical operation

retail.meaning: The sale of goods directly to the consumer, encompassing the storefronts, mail-order, websites, etc., and the corporate mechanisms, branding, advertising, etc. that support them.

retailer.meaning: A retail sales company or salesman.

retain.meaning: To keep in possession or use.

retell.meaning: To tell again, often differently, what one has read or heard; to paraphrase.

retina.meaning: The thin layer of cells at the back of the eyeball where light is converted into neural signals sent to the brain.

retire.meaning: The act of retiring, or the state of being retired.

retired.meaning: To stop working on a permanent basis, usually because of old age or illness.
retired.example: Having made a large fortune, he retired.

retreat.meaning: The act of pulling back or withdrawing, as from something dangerous, or unpleasant.

return.example: I expect the house to be spotless upon my return.

reunification.meaning: The unification of something that was previously divided; used especially of a country.

reunify.meaning: To unify again; to bring back together, or come back together, after separation.

reunion.meaning: The process or act of reuniting.
reunion.example: It was a tearful and heartfelt reunion as the trapped miners finally saw their dear loved ones again.

reveal.meaning: The outer side of a window or door frame; the jamb.

revelation.meaning: The act of revealing or disclosing.

revenge.meaning: Any form of personal retaliatory action against an individual, institution, or group for some alleged or perceived harm or injustice.

revenue.meaning: The income returned by an investment.

reverence.meaning: Veneration; profound awe and respect, normally in a sacred context.

reverse.example: We believed the Chinese weren't ready for us. In fact, the reverse was true.

review.meaning: A second or subsequent reading of a text or artifact in an attempt to gain new insights.
review.example: I need to make a review of the book before I can understand it.

riddle.meaning: A verbal puzzle, mystery, or other problem of an intellectual nature.
riddle.example: Here's a riddle: It's black, and white, and red all over. What is it?

ride.example: Can I have a ride on your bike?

rider.meaning: One who rides, often on a horse or a motorcycle.

ridge.meaning: The back of any animal; especially the upper or projecting part of the back of a quadruped.

ridiculous.example: It's ridiculous to charge so much for a little souvenir.

righteousness.meaning: The quality or state of being righteous.

right-hand.meaning: Of, relating to, or located on the right

rightly.meaning: In a right manner, correctly, justifiably.
rightly.example: I don't rightly know what he meant by that remark.

rim.meaning: An edge around something, especially when circular.

ring.meaning: (physical) A solid object in the shape of a circle.

ripe.meaning: A fruit or vegetable which has ripened.

rise.meaning: To move, or appear to move, physically upwards relative to the ground.

risk.meaning: A possible adverse event or outcome

risky.example: Investing in this start-up company could be risky.

ritual.meaning: Rite; a repeated set of actions
ritual.example: They carried out the ritual carefully.

rival.meaning: A competitor (person, team, company, etc.) with the same goal as another, or striving to attain the same thing. Defeating a rival may be a primary or necessary goal of a competitor.
rival.example: Chris is my biggest rival in the 400-metre race.

river.meaning: A large and often winding stream which drains a land mass, carrying water down from higher areas to a lower point, oftentimes ending in another body of water, such as an ocean or in an inland sea.
river.example: Occasionally rivers overflow their banks and cause floods.

road.meaning: A way used for travelling between places, originally one wide enough to allow foot passengers and horses to travel, now (US) usually one surfaced with asphalt or concrete and designed to accommodate many vehicles travelling in both directions. In the UK both senses are heard: a country road is the same as a country lane.

roadside.meaning: The area on either side of a road.
roadside.example: I pulled over to the roadside to check the map.

roam.meaning: To wander or travel freely and with no specific destination.

roar.meaning: A long, loud, deep shout, as of rage or laughter, made with the mouth wide open.

roast.meaning: A cut of meat suited to roasting

rotten.meaning: Of perishable items, overridden with bacteria and other infectious agents.
rotten.example: If you leave a bin unattended for a few weeks, the rubbish inside will turn rotten.

rough.meaning: The unmowed part of a golf course.

roughly.meaning: In a rough manner; without kindness, softness, or gentleness.

round.meaning: So as to form a circle or trace a circular path, or approximation thereof.

roundabout.meaning: (Australia and sometimes United States) A road junction at which traffic streams circularly around a central island.

route.meaning: A course or way which is traveled or passed.
route.example: The route was used so much that it formed a rut.

routine.meaning: A course of action to be followed regularly; a standard procedure.

row.meaning: A line of objects, often regularly spaced, such as seats in a theatre, vegetable plants in a garden etc.

royal.meaning: A royal person; a member of a royal family.

royalty.meaning: The rank, status, power or authority of a monarch.

rub.example: Give that lamp a good rub and see if any genies come out

rubber.meaning: Pliable material derived from the sap of the rubber tree; a hydrocarbon polymer of isoprene.

rubbish.example: The rubbish is collected every Thursday in Gloucester, but on Wednesdays in Cheltenham.

rubble.meaning: The broken remains of an object, usually rock or masonry.

rude.example: Karen broke up with Fred because he was often rude to her.

rug.meaning: A partial covering for a floor.

rugby.meaning: (usually uncountable) A form of football in which players can hold or kick an ovoid ball. The ball cannot be handled forwards and points are scored by touching the ball to the ground in the area past their opponent’s territory or kicking the ball between goalposts and over a crossbar.
rugby.example: The scrum is a distinctive element of rugby.

ruin.meaning: (sometimes in the plural) The remains of a destroyed or dilapidated construction, such as a house or castle.

rule.example: All participants must adhere to the rules.

ruler.meaning: A (usually rigid), flat, rectangular measuring or drawing device with graduations in units of measurement; a straightedge with markings.

runaway.meaning: A person or animal that runs away or has run away; a person, animal, or organization that escapes captivity or restrictions.
runaway.example: Runaway children are vulnerable to criminal exploitation.

sail.meaning: A piece of fabric attached to a boat and arranged such that it causes the wind to drive the boat along. The sail may be attached to the boat via a combination of mast, spars and ropes.

sailing.meaning: To be impelled or driven forward by the action of wind upon sails, as a ship on water; to be impelled on a body of water by steam or other power.

sailor.meaning: A person in the business of navigating ships or other vessels

salad.meaning: A food made primarily of a mixture of raw or cold ingredients, typically vegetables, usually served with a dressing such as vinegar or mayonnaise.

salary.meaning: A fixed amount of money paid to a worker, usually calculated on a monthly or annual basis, not hourly, as wages. Implies a degree of professionalism and/or autonomy.

salesman.meaning: A man whose job it is to sell things, either in a shop/store or elsewhere.

salesmanship.meaning: The skills and knowledge of how to sell.
salesmanship.example: The professional dealer's salesmanship was incredible, I was just looking but he managed to convince me to buy three times what I was considering buying over the next six months.

salesperson.meaning: A person whose job is to sell things, either in a shop/store or elsewhere.

saleswoman.meaning: A woman whose occupation it is to sell things.

salmon.meaning: One of several species of fish, typically of the Salmoninae subfamily, brownish above with silvery sides and delicate pinkish-orange flesh; they ascend rivers to spawn.

salon.meaning: A large room, especially one used to receive and entertain guests.

salsa.meaning: A spicy tomato sauce, often including onions and hot peppers.

salt.meaning: A common substance, chemically consisting mainly of sodium chloride (NaCl), used extensively as a condiment and preservative.

same.meaning: Not different or other; not another or others; not different as regards self; selfsame; identical.
same.example: Are you the same person who phoned me yesterday?

sample.meaning: A part or snippet of something taken or presented for inspection, or shown as evidence of the quality of the whole; a specimen.

sand.meaning: Rock that is ground more finely than gravel, but is not as fine as silt (more formally, see grain sizes chart), forming beaches and deserts and also used in construction.

sandal.meaning: A type of open shoe made up of straps or bands holding a sole to the foot

sandstone.meaning: A sedimentary rock produced by the consolidation and compaction of sand, cemented with clay etc.

sandwich.meaning: A dish or foodstuff where two or more slices of bread serve as the wrapper or container of some other food.

sanitation.meaning: The hygienic disposal or recycling of waste.

scared.meaning: To frighten, terrify, startle, especially in a minor way.
scared.example: Did it scare you when I said "Boo!"?

scarf.meaning: A long, often knitted, garment worn around the neck.
